<HEADLINE> Singapore Navy Orders Six French ACONIT Type Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Commander of the French frigate
ACONIT Monday confirmed here that the Singapore Navy has ordered
six warships of the ACONIT type and the acquisition will be made
before 2009.
</P>
<P>
During a press briefing on board the ship, Commander Benoit
Silve said that the first of the order will be constructed in
France and the other five will be assembled in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The commander noted that Singapore will own the largest fleet
of the ACONIT type ships as up to now only 14 such ships have been
built with five equipping the French navy, five bought by Saudi
Arabia and four exported to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The ACONIT, 125 meters in length and 15.4 meters in width and
capable of sailing at a speed of 25 nautical miles, belongs to the
last generation of La Fayette frigate class ships acquired by the
French Navy. Like its sister ships of the same class, namely the
La Fayette, the Surcouf, the Courbet and the Gue'pratte, the
ACONIT is a 3,600-ton ship with a long-rage and with a complement
of about 153, capable of engaging both surface as well as air
threat.
</P>
<P>
The ACONIT is described as "stealthy" because its geometrical
shapes and avoidance of all natural radar reflectors.
</P>
<P>
The French ACONIT sailed into Singapore water Monday from
Malaysia on a seven-month round the world mission (May 10 -
November 30) which has taken and will take her to 19 ports in 16
countries and areas.
</P>
<P>
During her call at Singapore, she will participate in joint
exercises with the Singapore navy and be open to the public for
three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
