<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania, Macedonia, Bulgaria to Step Up Anti-crime Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Albania, Macedonia and Bulgaria
have agreed to strengthen cooperation in combating organized cross-
border crimes, the Albanian news agency ATA reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
During a recent meeting in the resort city of Ohrid, southern
Macedonia, the interior ministers of the three countries agreed to
make joint efforts in cracking down on organized crimes of various
forms and carrying out common security measures.
</P>
<P>
The ministers called for substantiated tripartite cooperation,
saying it should not stay on paper or become lip service.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Albanian Interior Minister Spartak Poci and
his Macedonian counterpart, Dosta Dimovska, signed a cooperation
accord providing for stepped-up border checks to prevent entry of
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a similar document was signed between Albania and
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, border areas between the three southeastern
European countries have served as a major transit route for
illegal drugs and immigrants destined for western Europe.
</P>
<P>
Poci stressed that the campaign against drug-smuggling and
illegal immigration in the region needs not only strengthened
cooperation among Albania, Bulgaria and Macedonia, but also
collaboration with neighboring Greece, Turkey and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
