<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legally Blind Runyan Makes U.S. Olympic Track Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Marla Runyan, a legally blind
since she was nine, is on the U.S. Olympic team after taking third
in the women's 1,500 meters at the U.S. Olympic track and field
trials in Sacramento, California on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Unbelievable," said Runyan who finished third at 4 minutes 06.
44 seconds, behind winner Regina Jacobs in 4:01.01 and runner-up
Suzy Favor Hamilton 4:01.81.
</P>
<P>
A heptathlete at the U.S. Olympic trials in 1996, Runyan
becomes the first legally blind member of the U.S. Olympic team,
but she thinks of herself as an athlete first.
</P>
<P>
"I never think about my vision as much as the media does," said
Runyan, 31, who has macular degeneration, 20/300 vision and see
peripherally. "And I don't think my competitors do, either. My
vision is just a circumstance. I never really looked at it as a
barrier. I never said to myself I wanted to be the first legally
blind Olympian. I just said I wanted to be on an Olympic team."
</P>
<P>
Runyan had a clear strategy. "I was running for third," said
Runyan who finished ahead of Shayne Culpepper as the latter
clocked in 4:08.38.
</P>
<P>
Runyan was too injured to run for a month until a week ago, and
most of her training since June 9 has been in the pool or on an
elliptical running machine as she had had problems with her left
iliotibial band, which runs along the outside of the leg from hip
to knee.
</P>
<P>
Runyan spent about two weeks at the Olympic Training Center in
Colorado Springs for treatment. She did light track workouts in
the past week.
</P>
<P>
"She's a remarkable woman," said her coach Mike Manley, "She
has a tremendous physical gift, but she also has the mental
strength to overcome problems and focus on what she needs to do to
get where she wants." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
