<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanians to Seek Signature on Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian Professional
Association (JPA) will seek 2 million signatures to reject any
compensation or resettlement for Palestinian refugees and call for
their return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
Association sources said here Tuesday that the JPA, grouping
doctors, lawyers, engineers and other professionals, is also
planning a march to protest against the ongoing summit between U.S.
President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat at David Camp near Washington.
</P>
<P>
The trilateral summit is mainly focusing on Jerusalem,
Palestinian refugees, borders and water, the thorniest issues
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the JPA, known for its staunch anti-Israeli
stand, issued a sharply-worded statement against the three-day
summit, calling for a jihad (holy war) to liberate Palestinian
territories in stead of "holding negotiations in light of weakened
Arab positions and limitations imposed on Palestinian negotiators."
</P>
<P>
The JPA is apparently afraid that the David Camp summit will end
up with an agreement that falls short of taking into consideration
Jordan's interests, particularly on the Palestinian refugee issue.
</P>
<P>
Israel has reportedly said it was ready to allow 75,000
Palestinian refugees to return to their homeland, while the
remainder of the refugees would receive international aid and
settle down in countries where they are living now.
</P>
<P>
There are some 4.5 million Palestinians living in Jordan, Syria,
Lebanon and other Arab countries, as a result of the successive
Middle East wars since the creation of Israel in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is now hosting some 1.5 million Palestinian refugees,
most of them have been given Jordanian citizenship, but the
government supports their rights to choose between returning home
or staying in Jordan while asking for compensation from parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming
the second Arab country after Egypt to realize peace with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
However, anti-Israel sentiment could be easily felt among
Jordanians, over 60 percent of whom are of Palestinian origins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
