<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The United Nations has withdrawn its international
observers from southern Iraq, U.N. spokesman in Iraq George
Sommerwill told Xinhua on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sommerwill said that the U.N. began the operation on Sunday by
pulling out its staff from Basra, Misan, Thi-Qar and Qadissiyah in
southern Iraq.  For the time being, Iraqi staffers in the U.N.
team are continuing their work in the above-mentioned provinces.
(Iraq-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Syrian authorities have released three Jordanians who
had been labelled as political prisoners by Jordan and they will
return to Amman soon after obtaining travel documents, Jordanian
sources said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three were freed last weekend from Syrian prisons, one of
them was identified as 41-year-old Khalid Awad who had been
imprisoned for 12 years in the Tadmour jail in Syria, and the other
two preferred to remain unnamed.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to return to Amman after obtaining travel
documents from the Jordanian embassy in Damascus. (Syria-Jordanian
Prisoners)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A controversial former U.N. chief inspector said
here Tuesday that Iraq is back in the business of making weapons of
mass destruction. However, he admitted that he has no hard evidence
to support the accusation.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, former head of the now defunct United Nations
Special Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM), made the remarks to Israel
Radio after a meeting in the Israeli Knesset (parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee. (Israel-Iraq-Butler)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Emirates, the leading airline company of the United
Arab Emirates, has signed a contract with the European aviation
giant Airbus Industries for the purchase of three additional Airbus
A330 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The contract will raise the total number of A330s Emirates has
ordered to 21, according to a press release issued on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three A330s will be delivered in November and December this
year and March 2001 respectively. (UAE-Airbus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The demand for faster and more efficient network
technology is rising in the United Arab Emirates as e-commerce
takes hold in the region, according to a press release issued by
the Dubai World Trade Centre on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While the average penetration of the Internet in the Arab World
stood at 0.7 percent in February 2000, almost 10 percent of the
UAE's population are online and almost one quarter of all PCs in
the UAE are connected to the Internet, the press quoted Rowland
Griffiths, regional director of Cisco Systems in the Middle East
assaying. (UAE-Network) 
</P>
</TEXT>
