<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Cancels Trip to London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has cancelled a planned trip to London as the
Middle East Summit in Camp David entered its final phase on
Tuesday, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters that Albright had been
due to fly to London Tuesday night and speak to a lawyers'
conference in the British capital.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that President Bill Clinton was still planning to
travel to Japan on Wednesday to attend a Group of Eight nations
summit.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton was scheduled to depart aboard a helicopter at
8:40 a.m. EDT (1240 GMT) on Wednesday, then leave Dulles
International Airport aboard Air Force One for Tokyo at 9:10 a.m.
EDT (1310 GMT).
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman said that the accompanying press plane, which
had been due to leave on Tuesday evening, has been postponed until
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the press flight was delayed because the
White House did not want reporters to miss any possible
announcement on the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"The press plane is delayed until tomorrow morning so White
House people are not in the air 10 hours from some place when we
come out and say something," Lockhart said at a temporary media
center set up in an elementary school near Camp David, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that Clinton, who has been shuttling to mediate
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat for the past week, worked until 5 a.m. (0900 GMT)
and resumed consultations with his advisors on Tuesday morning
before meeting again with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Due to a strict news blackout imposed on the summit, the
spokesman refused to comment on the substance of the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
