<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Military Ask for Discussion on Base Used by U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Commander of the Ecuadoran Air Force
(FAE) General Oswaldo Dominguez said Tuesday the treaty for use of
Manta Air Base by U.S. military men must be discussed publicly.
</P>
<P>
On his part, delegate of the National Congress Leon Roldos
requested revision of the treaty for use of Manta Air Base, signed
in November 1999 between Ecuador and the United States because the
treaty wasn't explained at that time to a full Congress.
</P>
<P>
Roldos said the previous government's decision to grant
American troops use of Manta Air Base, situated on Ecuador's
northwest coast, was and is inadmissible and undue. He argued that
other Latin American countries have refused to allow American
military bases on their land.
</P>
<P>
According to Roldos, Manta Air Base means to be, in some way,
alternative for Panama Base.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Colonel Lucio Gutierrez, leader of the military
uprising on January 21, said Ecuador doesn't obtain any benefit
from the accord signed with the United States and, on the contrary,
could have unpredictable consequences.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadorians don't obtain any benefits from this covenant but
tens of thousands of displaced from Colombia who'll pass the
border, said the retired colonel.
</P>
<P>
As Ecuador's Foreign Ministry reported, the accord to last 10
years will have clear objectives like carrying air operations for
detention, monitoring, tracking and controlling of illegal air
drug-traffic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
