<HEADLINE> Dutch Firm to Buy France Telecom in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch leading telecoms
service KPN Telecom was garnering money to fund a buy-out of its
Belgian joint venture with France Telecom, local press reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch firm confirmed that it took interest in buying the 50-
percent stake it does not own of the Belgian mobile phone operator
KPN Orange.
</P>
<P>
"It is logical," said KPN spokesman Marinus Potman, "that we
are interested in the stake but we have no definite plans yet."
</P>
<P>
The ownership of KPN Orange has been in doubt since France
Telecom snapped up Orange in June.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources said on Tuesday that a loan is in the works
though the Amsterdam-based KPN Telecom did not confirm that it had
secured the loan.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources also said that the loan could be used to
finance KPN's investment in the third-generation mobile phone
services in Germany, Belgium and the Netherlands and could also be
used in financing KPN's payment to its Hong Kong partner Hutchison
Whampoa.
</P>
<P>
KPN has forged an alliance with Hutchison and Japan's NTT
DoCoMo to help expand mobile phone services in four of Europe's
third-generation mobile phone markets.
</P>
<P>
The three companies have planned to jointly bid for third-
generation, broadband Universal Mobile Telecommunications System
licenses in Germany, France, Belgium and possibly Italy.
</P>
