<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Passes "Marriage Penalty" Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate passed a "marriage
penalty" bill by a vote of 60-39 Tuesday that would cut 248
billion dollars in tax over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which is the centerpiece of the 792 billion dollars
Republican tax cut that Clinton vetoed last year, now heads for
negotiations between the House and Senate on a final measure that
could go to President Clinton for signature this week.
</P>
<P>
Republicans want the president to sign it before the party's
national political convention begins July 31 in Philadelphia to
draw public attention to their differences with Democrats on tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
"We will see who supports marriage-tax relief, and we will see
who thinks American families are not entitled to this relief,"
said Republican Senator William Roth, the Senate Finance Committee
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has said he could sign the measure into law only under
the condition that Congress also send him a bill creating a
prescription drug benefit in the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
Two single people enjoy wider tax brackets than a comparable
married couple in the U.S., resulting in an average tax bill 1,400
dollars higher for 25 million couples.  
</P>
</TEXT>
