<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bidding for Dutch UMTS Licenses Reaches 1.7 Bln Guilders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Bidding for the Dutch auction of
five third-generation mobile phone service licenses reached 1.7
billion Dutch guilders (721 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Telfort and KPN Mobile were the top bidders for licenses A and
B, with Telfort bid being 673.4 million guilders for license A of
the Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS) and KPN
Mobile bid being 672.7 million guilders for license B.
</P>
<P>
The bids surpassed the opening prices offered by the Dutch
government at 470 million guilders (202 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The licenses on offer will entitle holders to use allocated
frequencies for the provision of services until December 31, 2016.
The UMTS services turn mobile telephones into multimedia devices.
</P>
<P>
UMTS stands for universal mobile telecommunications standard,
the newest generation of cellular phone service. UMTS boasts of a
transmission speed 40 times faster than that of the existing GSM
standard.
</P>
<P>
The higher telecommunication speed makes possible new
capabilities such as mobile phone connection to the Internet and
video displays.
</P>
<P>
Eight companies have been allowed into the Dutch auction,
including five already having established telecoms services in the
Netherlands. The bidders were KPN Mobile, Libertel, Telfort,
Dutchtone, Ben, Nogenta Swedish Acquisition, Hutchison 3G
Netherlands and VersaTel.
</P>
<P>
KPN Mobile and Libertel are the largest and second largest
mobile phone operators in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
But two contenders, Nogenta Swedish Acquisition and Ben,
withdrew from the auction.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch Treasury has canceled a July bond issue because of
anticipated UMTS license revenues.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is the second European country after Britain to
have auctioned UMTS licenses. In April, the British government got
22.5 billion pounds (34 billion dollars) from the auction sales of
five UMTS licenses, more than five times the sum previously
expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
