<HEADLINE> Oil Price Rise Affects C.America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The surge of oil prices has
affected all Central American countries, specially El Salvador,
which registered greatest gasoline increases, said the Secretariat
of Central American Economic Integration (SIECA) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Super gasoline went up in the last three-month period a little
over 20 percent and Regular rose 10 percent in El Salvador, the
SIECA said in a report made known Tuesday by Costa Rica Petroleum
Refinery (Recope).
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica registered the lowest rise, almost 8 percent in
Super gasoline and 8.3 percent in Regular, according to the SIECA.
</P>
<P>
After El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras and Guatemala in this
order were the countries that registered biggest increases in
hydrocarburate prices.
</P>
<P>
The gallon of Super gasoline was worth in El Salvador at this
July's beginning, an equivalent to 2.63 dollars, while Regular was
2.21 dollars. In Costa Rica, these prices were 2.34 and 2.22
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Recope President Gerardo Rudin considered possible for coming
months a reduction of oil prices following the decision of
producers of an increase in extraction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
