<HEADLINE> UAE Takes up Three Additional Airbus A330s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Emirates, the leading airline
company of the United Arab Emirates, has signed a contract with the
European aviation giant Airbus Industries for the purchase of three
additional Airbus A330 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The contract will raise the total number of A330s Emirates has
ordered to 21, according to a press release issued on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three A330s will be delivered in November and December this
year and March 2001 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The A330-200 is gradually replacing Emirates' fleet of Airbus
A310-300 and A300-600R aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Emirates is Airbus Industries' largest Middle East customer. It
had ordered 18 A330s, powered by Rolls-Royce Trent 700 engines. Of
these 18 orders, nine have already been delivered, with the
remainder scheduled to join the fleet by April 2002.
</P>
<P>
Emirates was also the first airlines in the Middle East to take
delivery of the A330-200 and the first to order it with Rolls-Royce
Trent 700 engines.
</P>
<P>
According to the newly-signed agreement, the value of the first
two A330s was 142.9 million euros (about 165 million U.S. dollars).
It is also one of the first long-term fundings worldwide to be
disbursed in the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
