<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Hungarian bus manufacturer Ikarus has appealed to the
Turkish authorities to support a joint venture in the bus
production in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ikarus' Turkey-desk manager Erzebet Loczy said although Turkey
is an important market, Ikarus cannot sell buses there due to stiff
competition from Asian companies and a major disadvantage in prices
despite good quality.
</P>
<P>
He said this could be overcome by producing the buses in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's first nuclear power plant project will
probably be postponed for a long time amid controversy between the
government and the bidding consortia.
</P>
<P>
The Energy and Natural Resources Ministry should select the
winning consortium by July 24. However, the announcement is set to
be put off for at least another year due to the Treasury's
reluctance to provide guarantees for the financing of the 5-
billion-U.S. dollar plant to be built in Akkuyu in the southern
province of Mersin.
</P>
<P>
But bidders would not accept another delay, warning to withdraw
their bids in case of another postponement.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Increasing poverty and the erosion of purchasing power
in Turkey are attracting greater attention as the government's
anti-inflation program puts extraordinary pressure on wages and
farm produce prices.
</P>
<P>
Unequal income distribution and low growth rates are also shown
as the basic reasons for the fragility of the Turkish economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that there are 20 million people living
below the poverty line, with 5 million of these suffering from
hunger.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Finance Minister Avraham Shochat announced
on Monday plans to continue reducing purchase taxes on electrical
appliances. Shochat refused to mention any figures for the promised
reductions or to say what highly-taxed electrical appliances will
be included in his plans.
</P>
<P>
Current purchase taxes range from 30 percent to 55 percent on
large home appliances such as refrigerators, washing machines and
stoves and between 65 percent to 85 percent on luxury items and
home entertainment equipment such as dishwashers, stereos and video
recorders.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Postal Authority has issued a tender
for a computer company to devise a program that will enable it to
sell stamps via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Officials estimate that the authority will complete preparations
to sell stamps via an Internet site by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
A program is being developed that will allow customers to
download stamps from the authority's web site after paying for them
via credit card, print them out on a home printer and stick them on
the envelopes.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Bank of Israel issued a report on Monday
calling for increasing the minimum wage by adopting standards for
the calculation of such salaries.
</P>
<P>
It noted that over 50 percent of employers surveyed pay their
workers less than the minimum wage, currently 2,798 shekels (about
700 dollars). The sum is updated on April 1 each year, based on 47.
5 percent of the average salary.
</P>
<P>
One of the recommendations raised is to automatically link
salaries to the consumer price index, which would maintain their
real value. Another option is to link the minimum wage to the
median salary.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish company, Ezinc Metal Sanayi A.S., which is
based in central Kayseri province, is exporting solar collectors to
European and African countries.
</P>
<P>
Ezinc Metal Sanayi A.S. Deputy General Director, Hakan Alas,
told reporters Tuesday that they had exported 1.3 million dollars
worth of copper and aluminium solar collectors to Spain, Italy,
France, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Austria, Egypt, Libya,
Tunisia, Saudi Arabia, Yemen and Jordan in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
Alas said that they plan to increase their solar collectors
exports to 3 million dollars by the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Introduce Tougher Traffic Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian authorities will introduce
tougher traffic laws, including a maximum fine of 1,400 U.S.
dollars on a traffic law violator, to reduce road accidents in the
kingdom, police said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new laws are expected to go into effect on August 1 with the
most severe fines to be imposed on hit-and-run drivers, those
driving under the influence of drugs or alcohol or transporting
poisonous or explosive materials without proper authorization.
</P>
<P>
The maximum fine for a traffic wrongdoer will be increased to 1,
000 Jordanian dinars( 1,400 dollars) from the current 50 dinars (70
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new measures are part of the efforts by the government to
curb the alarming rate of road accidents, which claimed 612 lives
in 1999 alone in the kingdom with a population of 4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
Officials blamed the leading causes of the accidents on
ignorance of traffic laws, speeding, wrongful overtaking, poor
driving habits, driving under the influence of alcohol and poor
vehicle conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, critics blamed the government for poor road
construction and maintenance and the police are also criticized for
failing to implement traffic laws to the letter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
