<HEADLINE> Demand for Network Technology Rises in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The demand for faster and more
efficient network technology is rising in the United Arab Emirates
as e-commerce takes hold in the region, according to a press
release issued by the Dubai World Trade Centre on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While the average penetration of the Internet in the Arab World
stood at 0.7 percent in February 2000, almost 10 percent of the
UAE's population are online and almost one quarter of all PCs in
the UAE are connected to the Internet, the press quoted Rowland
Griffiths, regional director of Cisco Systems in the Middle East as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The press said that revenue for Internet Economy companies grew
at an annual rate of 11 percent from 1998 to 1999 in the United
States, nearly three times the growth rate of the economy as a
whole for the same period. Additionally, the stock value of the 200
largest U.S.-based public network companies topped 5 trillion U.S.
dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason to doubt that similar trends are occurring
in the UAE. As E-commerce takes hold in the country, the demand for
faster and more efficient network technology continues to climb,"
the release added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Gitex 2000, the third largest IT event in the world
and the Middle East's largest and most important IT event will be
held at the Dubai World Trade Centre in October. It will feature a
wide range of the most advanced network options and the wire
technology to support them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
