<HEADLINE> Nigerian Peacekeeper Killed in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
announced Tuesday a Nigerian peacekeeper in Sierra Leone was
killed by rebels from the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) when
his patrol came under fire.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place Sunday near Rogberi Junction in
western Sierra Leone but his body was not recovered until Monday,
the U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said here.
</P>
<P>
The president of the U.N. Security Council, Patricia Durrant
of Jamaica, read a statement to the press here that Council
members expressed condolences to the family of the Nigerian
soldier and the Nigerian Government.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials said that there was no evidence to suggest the
incident was a retaliatory move for the weekend operation in which
Indian, Ghanaian and Nigerian soldiers rescued 233 U.N.
peacekeepers who had been encircled by rebels in Kailahun, the RUF
stronghold in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said that uprooted civilian fleeing the rebels were
suffering from a lack of water and poor sanitation conditions near
the town of Mile 91, east of the capital Freetown, where some 60,
000 people were gathered.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Food Program is distributing food and trying to find
new campsites, he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has some 13,000 peacekeepers in Sierra
Leone, sent to monitor the Lome Peace Accord, signed by the Sierra
Leonean Government and the RUF in July last year in a bid to end
the civil war which broke out in 1991. However, rebels broke the
peace accord by attacking U.N. soldiers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
