<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF Support Debt Relief for Benin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Tuesday agreed to support a
debt relief package for Benin under the enhanced Heavily Indebted
Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative.
</P>
<P>
Total relief from all of Benin's creditors is worth around 460
million U.S. dollars, according to statements from the two lending
institutions.
</P>
<P>
In net present value (NPV) terms, the value of the relief was
estimated at 265 million dollars, or 31 percent of the total NPV
of the western African country's debt outstanding at end-1998
after the full use of traditional debt relief mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's International Development Association (IDA)
and the IMF will start providing interim debt relief by August 1,
2000. The IMF will contribute 24.3 million dollars to the package
and the IDA 124.3 million dollars over the full life of Benin's
debts.
</P>
<P>
Under the enhanced HIPC Initiative, countries with a
satisfactory track record of macroeconomic and structural policy
implementation and a NPV of external debt exceeding 150 percent of
exports are eligible to receive debt relief.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, Benin's debt-to-export ratio was 218
percent. With overall debt relief of 265 million dollars, that
ratio will be brought down to 150 percent by 2011 and under 100
percent in the ensuing years.
</P>
<P>
Benin will receive the remainder of its debt relief from all
its creditors once it drafts what is known in HIPC terms as a "
poverty reduction strategy paper", a document expected to be
completed by April 2001, according to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
To date, nine countries, Benin, Bolivia, Burkina Faso, Honduras,
Mauritania, Mozambique, Senegal, Tanzania and Uganda, are
receiving, or are about to receive, debt relief from the World
Bank and the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also approved Tuesday a three-year arrangement for
Benin under the Poverty Reduction and Growth Facility in a total
of 35.7 million dollars to support the government's 2000-03
economic program.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the program are to achieve real gross
domestic product (GDP) growth of 5-6 percent and contain inflation
below 3 percent. The country's real GDP growth was estimated to
have risen to about 5 percent in 1999 from 4.5 percent in 1998,
and was projected to increase to 5.6 percent in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
