<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Saudi-Kuwait Maritime Border Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq fully rejects the maritime
border deal between Saudi Arabia and Kuwait as it "does not respect
Iraq's legitimate rights," an Iraqi foreign ministry spokesman said
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq will not recognize any demarcation of a maritime border
that does not take into consideration Iraq's legitimate rights,"
the spokesman said in a statement carried by the official Iraqi
News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait signed the maritime border deal on July
2 over the demarcation of maritime border of the Gulf waterway and
through the Dorra gas field which is claimed by Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The deal would enable Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to take a common
stand in negotiating with Iran in dividing the area's rich oil and
gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, as one of the Gulf countries, shares maritime borders with
both Kuwait and Iran, said the spokesman, adding that any maritime
border deal "neglecting Iraq's legitimate rights" is not binding on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between Iraq and Saudi Arabia and Kuwait
have been frozen since Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which
triggered the 1991 Gulf War to drive Iraqi occupation troops out of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
