<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, U.S. to Explore for Off-shore Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The state-run Turkish Petroleum
Corp. (TPAO) and a U.S. oil company El Paso Energy will explore for
natural gas in the southern Iskenderun and Mersin gulfs.
</P>
<P>
TPAO and El Paso will sign a partnership agreement in Ankara on
Wednesday, reported the semi-official Anatolia News Agency on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The pact is expected to be signed by Osman Demirag, chairman of
TPAO Executive Board and general director, and John B. Holmes,
director of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the draft agreement, TPAO and El Paso will
carry out seismic research in shallow and deep waters in Mersin and
Iskenderun gulfs in the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, El Paso sealed an agreement with German-Italian partner
Geo Prakla company for the seismic researches that will be launched
in August.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that El Paso will collect deep-sea seismic data in
Iskenderun and Mersin gulfs. If necessary, the dimensions of the
researches will be increased.
</P>
<P>
The data acquired in the seismic research foreseen to be
concluded by the end of 2000, will be estimated by El Paso.
</P>
<P>
Two wells in Mersin and Iskenderun gulfs will be drilled in July
2001. The number of wells can be increased in accordance with the
results of seismic researches.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there are signs indicating natural gas
deposits in the sea off the coast.
</P>
<P>
El Paso will spend at least 20 million U.S. dollars for two
wells and if no natural gas or oil are determined, TPAO and El Paso
will share the expenditures of further operations, according to the
draft agreement.
</P>
<P>
El Paso wants to produce electricity by constructing a station
in the region if natural gas is found in Iskenderun and Mersin
gulfs.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, poor in fossil fuels, largely relies on imports from
oil- and natural gas-producing countries to meet the ever-growing
domestic demand for energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
