<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Families in Israel Closer to Receive More Allowances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Labor and Welfare Committee
of Israeli parliament Tuesday endorsed, amid heat debate, more
child allowances for families with five or more children, pushing
the large-family bill further on the way to becoming law.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill that already passed the preliminary and first
readings in the Knesset (parliament) and needs two more readings to
become law, from the fifth child on, each kid can get 250 shekels
(about 60 U.S. dollars) more child allowances to raise the total
sum to 850 shekels (about 200 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The birth grant for mothers who gave birth to more than five
children will also increase.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the committee scrapped an original clause in
the bill calling for big discounts in municipal taxes for families
of five children or more. It also dropped the proposal to extend
child allowances from the current age of 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chair David Tal from the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party
said the bill is a step toward better social status for large
families. "This is not a bill for any one sector. I believe it is a
good bill for all the citizens of Israel."
</P>
<P>
The bill met strong opposition from treasury officials who said
that the bill could cost 480 million shekels (about 120 million
dollars) out of the strained state budget.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Paritzky from the secular Shinui Party charged that the
ultra-Orthodox Party and their Knesset members are pushing the bill
for the big families in their constituencies.
</P>
<P>
"They now pass the law in the committee to be prepared for the
second and third readings in the parliament that will take from the
tax payers, from parents who work with one child, two children,
three children, from parents who contribute to this country by
serving in the army, by sending their children to the army, half a
billion shekels only to produce children," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an outrageous law. It is a disgrace to the parliament,
that such a law has been put on the table, not to mention the fact
that it passed the first reading." Paritzky said.
</P>
<P>
The large-family bill has aroused strong reaction in the Israeli
society. The most papular Israeli newspaper Yediot Ahronot said in
an earlier editorial that despite the fact the bill was intended as
an egalitarian arrangement to improve the financial status of all
families, every intelligent person knows that its true
beneficiaries are ultra-Orthodox families which typically have many
children.
</P>
<P>
The paper cautioned that if the bill is passed, the
discrimination against secular families, which usually have no more
than three children will be even greater.
</P>
<P>
The editor slammed the legislators from the Shas, the third
largest party with 17 seats in the 120-member Knesset, as
exploiting their political strength to squeeze more and more from
the public coffer on behalf of voters who contribute nothing to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
