<HEADLINE> Arab FMs to Meet to Finalize Details on Regular Summits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of five Arab
countries will meet early September to discuss a mechanism for the
holding an Arab summit on a regular basis, Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Egypt, Oman, Syria, Tunisia and Yemen,
which form a committee in charge of handling the issue, will meet
on September 2 to finalize the details, including the venue and
timing of the proposed regular summit, Abdel-Meguid said in an
interview with Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will submit their proposals to the 114th session
of the league's Foreign Ministers Council on September 3. The
council is expected to adopt the proposals.
</P>
<P>
Despite frequent talks about regular summits, aimed at seeking
common stands on key issues related to the Arab world, only one
summit has been held since the 1991 Gulf War, which was prompted by
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The meeting, held in Cairo in 1996,
excluded Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
During its meeting early last month, the five-way committee
proposed a summit on yearly basis in March next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
