<HEADLINE> Former Inspector Claims Iraq Back to Make Mass-Destruction Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A controversial former U.N. chief
inspector said here Tuesday that Iraq is back in the business of
making weapons of mass destruction. However, he admitted that he
has no hard evidence to support the accusation.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, former head of the now defunct United Nations
Special Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM), made the remarks to Israel
Radio after a meeting in the Israeli Knesset (parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee.
</P>
<P>
There is evidence "to the effect" that Iraq, now "awash with
money," is reproducing biological, chemical weapons again, said the
Australian, who was accused by Iraq of helping plant United States
spies in his inspection teams in charge of disarming Iraq of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Butler left the UNSCOM in June, 1999 after his contract expired.
</P>
<P>
He admitted, however, that because the inspection had been
suspended since the U.S. and Britain launched the four-night
Operation Desert Fox air strikes against Iraq in December 1998, he
has no concrete evidence for his claims.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is also collecting uranium for making nuclear weapons and
it will have nuclear warheads within 12 months if it has relevant
materials, claimed Butler, who is now a diplomat in residence at
the Council of Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz told him, while
he was still involved in the disarming of Iraq, that Iraq has
biological weapons "dealing with the Zionist entity (Israel)."
</P>
<P>
The successful launching of long-range Shahab-3 missile last
Saturday by Iran, with whom Iraq fought a bloody war in 1980-1988,
will only stir up Iraq's ambition to produce more mass-destruction
weapons to counteract the military development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Butler appealed to the United Nations Security Council to stop
Iraq form producing biological, chemical and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission
(UNMOVIC), which replaced the UNSCOM later last year, has yet to
begin its fieldwork in Iraq as Iraq refused to cooperate with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Israel regards Iraq as a major threat in the region. During the
1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait a year
earlier, Iraq launched Scud missiles against Israeli targets but
caused no casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
