<HEADLINE> S.African Airport Hit by Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A small explosive device went
off after 2:00 p.m. on Tuesday at Cape Town International Airport,
South Africa, causing minor damage but no injuries.
</P>
<P>
Airport manager Hennie Taljaard said staff initially thought
it was thunder, but further investigation found a small explosive
device had detonated in a dustbin between the international and
domestic departure halls.
</P>
<P>
Taljaard said no one was injured, nor were any cars parked
nearby damaged in any way. Initial reports that the explosion was
the result of a car bomb were discounted.
</P>
<P>
Police closed off both roads leading to the airport after the
explosion while bomb squad members sifted through the debris and
checked for further devices. Police believed that the blast was
linked with urban "terrorists".
</P>
<P>
These "terrorists" were attempting to ward off tourists,
Western Cape safety and security official Mark Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
He said there were 180 surveillance cameras at the airport and
police were studying the tapes for evidence.
</P>
<P>
All flights were reportedly running as scheduled and no delays
were anticipated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
