<HEADLINE> Poverty, AIDS Worsen Children's Situation in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The general situation for Kenyan
children has been worsened in the past ten years due to poverty
and AIDS problems, according to a U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
"The under-five mortality rate has increased from 99 per 1000
live births in 1994 to 117 per 1,000 live births in 1998," the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) Representative to Kenya
Nicholas Alipui said Tuesday while officially launching the UNICEF
's annual report The Progress of Nations 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, malnutrition continues to plague Kenyan children at
a high rate of between 22 percent to 37 percent despite the
promise that children would thrive and grow to their maximum
potential through good nutrition, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya has made commendable efforts but those have been
insufficient since we can not report progress in any of these
areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that rapidly increasing poverty, a rapidly
growing HIV/AIDS crisis and a rapidly expanding drought emergency
are major causes for the plight of Kenyan children.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS is increasing mortality among children and young adults
and is likely to reduce life expectancy drastically in Kenya
unless stopped now," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The response to the epidemic should be on many fronts --
through information, education, empowerment of women and girls,
communication, practice and behavior change on the part of
individuals as well as society at large, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
