<HEADLINE> Liberia Discusses Border Issues With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Liberia has renewed border talks
with neighboring Sierra Leone and Guinea, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a senior Liberian government official as
saying that the meeting of the Mano River Union Security Council,
kicked off Monday evening, came after the recent border raids by
Liberian dissidents from Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone and Liberia set up the Mano River Union in 1973 to
boost bilateral cooperation between the two countries and Guinea
joined the union later.
</P>
<P>
Liberia and Sierra Leone have since then been ravaged by civil
wars and mutual suspicion has dominated the relationship between
the two west African countries.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone accuses Liberia of supporting the rebel
Revolutionary United Front by engaging in diamond-for-armament
business, while Liberia accuse Sierra Leone and Guinea of
harboring its dissidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
