<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Donates Medicine to Pipeline Explosion Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has donated
drugs worth 67 million naira (about 670,000 U.S. dollars) for
victims of the recent oil pipeline explosions in the eastern
Delta State, according to a press release from the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Tim Menakaya provided the donations during his
weekend visit to the accident center at the University of Benin
Teaching Hospital, where the victims are being treated.
</P>
<P>
Menakaya said the donation was part of the efforts of his
ministry and other collaborating agencies to save the lives of
those people that were affected in the unfortunate explosions.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that his ministry would give all the
necessary financial and logistics support to improve facilities at
the accident center to upgrade it to one of the best emergency
unit, with a specialized burns unit to carry out constructive
surgery.
</P>
<P>
The recent oil pipeline explosions which resulted from
vandalism in some villages near Warri of the oil-producing Delta
State has claimed more than 300 lives. 
</P>
