<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement on Jerusalem Near Completion: Israeli Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the Palestinians are
on the verge of reaching an agreement on Jerusalem at the Camp
David summit in the United States, Israel Radio reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is one of the key issues in the Israeli-Palestinian
final-status talks. Israel has insisted that the city is its "
eternal and united capital," while the Palestinians said they will
declare an independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its
capital.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted an Israeli source in Washington as saying that
the Israeli and Palestinian negotiating teams have spent a lot of
time on Tuesday discussing the Jerusalem issue and are about to
reach an agreement on this most difficult problem.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Israel would take full control of the city
and its surrounding areas while granting the Palestinians control
of the Arab neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The surrounding areas include the settlements of Ma'ale Adumim
in the east of the city, Givat Ze'ev in the northwest and Gush
Etsyon southwest of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
But the report quoted a Palestinian source as saying that
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who is at Camp David with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.S. President Bill Clinton, has made
it clear from the beginning of the summit that East Jerusalem
should be put under full Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders held lengthy meetings Tuesday to try to work
out a framework agreement on all the key issues of the Israeli-
Palestinian final-status talks, which also include borders,
refugees and Jewish settlements, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Knesset (parliament) Speaker Avraham Burg said here
Tuesday that Israel could reach the framework agreement with the
Palestinians at the Camp David summit, but the outcome might not be
clear until the last minute.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Ehud Barak's mood is very cautious but
determined as the Camp David summit enters its decisive state,"
Burg said.
</P>
<P>
"I would say it is the highest motivation I have ever seen in
any Israeli leader to make such a risky breakthrough in order to
bring peace for the people of Israel and the Palestinians," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"In Israel, usually the best solutions come at the last
minute, ...with the Palestinian side, they are coming sometimes
even after the last moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which began last Tuesday, is aimed at working out a
framework agreement on key issues ahead of the September target for
a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Washington said the peace talks at the summit had
been escalated on Tuesday due to Clinton's anticipated departure
for Japan to attend the ecomonic summit of the Group of Eight,
which comprises the seven richest countries plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his advisors are pressing the Israeli and
Palestinian sides to reach a framework agreement before his
departure Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If an agreement or declaration is not reached by then, the two
sides could decide whether to suspend the talk or to continue at
Camp David and wait for Clinton's return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
