<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Rise 0.6 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices jumped 0.6
percent in June, chiefly reflecting surging gasoline prices and a
record rise in the cost of natural gas, the Labor Department
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted advance in the Consumer Price Index,
the most closely watched inflation gauge, came after prices rose
just 0.1 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
After falling sharply in May, energy prices shot up 5.6 percent
in June, the largest increase since April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices rose 8.8 percent last month, the biggest
increase since March. Prices for natural gas increased by a record
7.8 percent, surpassing the previous record in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Food prices, after rising sharply in May, increased by a slim 0.
1 percent in June as falling prices for fruit, dairy products and
poultry helped blunt rising prices for beef and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the "core"
rate of inflation rose just 0.2 percent in June, for the third
month in a row, suggesting that most other prices were under
control.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, overall consumer prices have been rising at
an annual rate of 4.2 percent, compared with a 2.7 percent
increase for all of last year. The pickup in this year's prices is
mostly a result of rising energy costs.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the last 13 months to slow economic growth and keep inflation in
check.
</P>
<P>
Some economic reports have suggested that the Fed's rate
increases are working to slow economic growth. Given that, some
economists expect the central bank to leave rates unchanged at its
meeting on August 22.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government reported that inflation at the
wholesale level rose a sharp 0.6 percent in June, mostly limited
to soaring energy prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
