<HEADLINE> British PM To Assure Japan on Euro policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
will seek to reassure his Japanese counterpart Yoshiro Mori this
week about Britain's policy on the euro currency, Blair's official
spokesman said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Alastair Campbell said Blair would set out Britain's commitment
in principle to join the euro, subject to passing economic tests
and approval in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister will use bilateral talks with Mori in Tokyo
on Thursday to explain his government's euro stance, addressing
fears that some major investors in Britain may switch production
to the eurozone, he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting comes only weeks after Britain's ambassador in
Japan, Stephen Gomersall, warned of disinvestment unless investors
are reassured on the euro policy.
</P>
<P>
A report said Gomersall urged Blair to use his trip to Japan to
offer "tea and sympathy" on the euro policy.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said the two leaders would tackle the euro issue
before they fly to the Group of Eight summit, to be held in
Okinawa, southern Japan, from Friday to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"There isn't a fixed agenda for the Japan bilateral (talks)yet,
" Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
"But in relation to the single currency, (Blair) will take the
opportunity to make sure the Japanese understand what the policy
is. Japanese inward investors understand that position but there's
no harm in the prime minister continuing to set it out," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
