<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Electricity Prices Show Downward Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Electricity prices showed a
general downward trend across the European Union (EU) in January
this year for both households and industrial consumers compared to
the figures in January 1998, the EU statistical office Eurostat
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the two-year period, electricity prices went down in
most of the EU countries because the bloc's 15 member states have
implemented new market rules since January 1, 1998 to liberalize
electricity markets.
</P>
<P>
Most of EU households, regardless of their volume of
consumption, benefited from a decrease in the price for
electricity between January 1998 and January 2000. According to
Eurostat, households or domestic consumers are broken down into
three categories - small, medium and large consumers.
</P>
<P>
The highest overall decreases in prices were in Finland and
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands stood out as the only EU member states where
electricity prices increased for all categories, by respectively
15 percent for small, 5 percent for medium and 4 percent for large
consumers. In Ireland, a significant rise was registered for large
consumers (20 percent) but prices were unchanged for the two other
categories.
</P>
<P>
A special situation arose in Italy: prices for medium and large
domestic consumers went down by around 10 percent but jumped at
the same time by 40 percent for small consumers, as a more
equitable tariff structure was implemented.
</P>
<P>
All the other member states recorded a general and moderate
drop of less than 5 percent, according to Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, industrial consumers in most of the EU countries
also witnessed a decrease in prices. The drop was specially high
in Germany, followed by Sweden, Portugal and Finland.
</P>
<P>
Prices for small industrial consumers also dropped
significantly in the Netherlands and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Greece was the only EU member with an overall price increase of
3 percent over the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
