<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Frees 3 Jordanian Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Syrian authorities have released
three Jordanians who had been labelled as political prisoners by
Jordan and they will return to Amman soon after obtaining travel
documents, Jordanian sources said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three were freed last weekend from Syrian prisons, one of
them was identified as 41-year-old Khalid Awad who had been
imprisoned for 12 years in the Tadmour jail in Syria, and the other
two preferred to remain unnamed.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to return to Amman after obtaining travel
documents from the Jordanian embassy in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Imad Sharqawi, a prominent Jordanian lawyer, said he expected
more Jordanian political prisoners to be released soon from Syrian
prisons after Bashar al-Assad was sworn in as Syrian president on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bashar had promised earlier to declare a public amnesty after he
becomes president, said Sharqawi, who was heading a Jordanian
committee lawyers, which is seeking the release of some 650
Jordanian and Palestinian prisoners from Syria.
</P>
<P>
Sharqawi believed that they were arrested mostly on charges of
being members of political parties, especially the Muslim
Brotherhood and radical Palestinian factions, while some others
were accused of serving Jordan's General Intelligence Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
