<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPLP Leaders End Summit with Maputo Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state from member
countries of the Community of the Portuguese-speaking Countries (
CPLP) ended their third summit on Tuesday in the Mozambican
capital Maputo, with the issue of the final statement known as the
Maputo Declaration.
</P>
<P>
According to the final statement of the two-day summit, the
development of education, training, science and technology in the
African Portuguese-speaking countries is considered crucial for
the further economic and social development of the African
countries that are still facing difficult economic and social
situations.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said that centers for research and training in
the Portuguese language will be respectively set up in Cape Verde,
Mozambique and Angola. Meanwhile Portugal and Brazil will
increase their financing for the CPLP's Special Fund, the Angolan
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement announced that Brazil will assume the
organization's rotating leadership for the following two years
with the Brazilian official Dulce Pereira elected unanimously as
the Executive Secretary of CPLP.
</P>
<P>
According to the Brazilian President Fernando Cardoso and the
new executive secretary, among priorities set by Brazil for its
CPLP mandate are a multilateral campaign against AIDS and the
creation of a program for the formation of 120 diplomats from the
group of seven-nations spanning three continents.
</P>
<P>
The summit also decided that the next CPLP summit will be held
in Brazil in the year of 2002, while Sao Tome and Principe will
host the mid-term Council of Ministers of CPLP in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Portuguese-speaking world, expressed in the
declaration their support for the full independence of East Timor
and the elections planned in the territory next year.
</P>
<P>
Timorese leader Xanana Gusmao, attending the Maputo summit as
an observer, said his country would adopt Portuguese as its "
official language" and hoped to join the CPLP soon as its eighth
member state. In the Declaration of Maputo, the summit also
praised Angola for "its efforts to combat subversion and re-
establish peace" in the context of the aborted 1994 Lusaka Peace
Protocol. It blamed the new eruption of war in Angola on "Jonas
Savimbi and his followers" in the rebel movement, namely the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), for
not having "fulfilled commitments" taken under the peace agreement
six years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
