<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Web Products Going Mobile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A new class of portable, Web-
based products will allow us to surf the Internet without having
to park ourselves at a desk over the next few years, a U.S.
scientist predicted in the latest issue of The Futurist.
</P>
<P>
"The Net has a larger place in the world than the desktop,"
said Mark Stefik, a scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto research
center. He predicted a new class of mobile, Web-based products,
including:
</P>
<P>
-- The personal document reader. This interactive, lightweight
digital display could allow people to watch the news or read
downloaded articles on the go.
</P>
<P>
-- The hiker's companion. This pocket-sized device would be
tied in to the Global Positioning System(GPS) so hikers would
always know where they are. In addition, it could retrieve
information from the Internet about the weather and trail
conditions. It could also summon help in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
-- The Web suit. This would be a radio-networked collection of
wearable devices for computing and browsing the Web. A pair of
special glasses would display information on a virtual screen in
front of a user's eyes -- but still allow people to see the real
world. The Web suit could be set up to respond to voice commands,
or it could be accessed through a keyboard worn on the forearm.
</P>
<P>
Stefik said that technological advances are bring these devices
closer to reality. The advances include improvements in displays,
increasing bandwidth, and longer-lasting batteries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photodynamic Therapy May Become Safer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Photodynamic therapy (PDT), a
treatment for cancers and other diseases, may become safer in the
future, reported the latest issue of The Futurist.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at Destiny Pharma in England have developed a
combination of new photosensitive chemicals and light sources that
ensure the potentially toxic, light-sensitive chemicals are not
left behind in the body, according a Futurist report.
</P>
<P>
PDT starts with an injection of light-sensitive chemicals into
a patient's bloodstream. The chemicals are absorbed by the body's
tissue, including the diseased tissue.
</P>
<P>
When a penetrating light is directed at the diseased tissue, it
reacts with the light-sensitive chemicals to produce a toxic
substance that kills the diseased tissue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Registers Trade Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia witnessed increasing
momentum in both imports and exports for the first half of this
year, the state statistics bureau said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia's foreign trade over the period reached 471.8 million
U.S. dollars, with 209.7 million dollars in exports and 262.1
million in imports.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a 140-million-dollar increase from last
year's level, with a 71.8-million dollar rise in exports, a 68.5-
million dollar rise in imports and a 3.3-million dollar decrease
in trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to higher copper prices at the international market,
Mongolia's exports of copper powder rocketed 54.7 percent in the
period under review. Exports of livestock raw materials also
enjoyed a considerable hike.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia trades with more than 50 countries, with China
remaining its biggest trading partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
