<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Drug Cheaters Go for Oympic Medals without Punishment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The USOC has evaded its responsibility to screen and discipline
those cheaters in its quest to produce medal-winning athletes,
said Wade Exum in his 30-page complaint filed in the U.S. District
Court in Denver.
</P>
<P>
Although no athletes were named, the lawsuit said that Exum
knows of competitors who tested positive for performance-enhancing
drugs in the Olympic trials and went on to win medals at the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
In the lawsuit, Exum said his anti-drug efforts were "willfully
and repeatedly undermined" by the committee's "unwillingness to
adopt an anti-doping program that had any real probability of
preventing athletic doping and protecting the health and well-
being of American athletes."
</P>
<P>
The USOC's real interest is "procuring gold medalists who
perform not just superbly, but who realize superhuman achievements,
" the suit said, adding that the USOC "knows that to achieve these
superhuman records, doping must occur."
</P>
<P>
It further pointed out that Exum was told to mind his own
business when he raised concerns that non-doctors were given keys
to what the suit calls "a pharmacopeia" in the USOC's Sports
Medicine Division and allowed to dispense the medicines to
athletes.
</P>
<P>
Exum is "aware of documentation" that will support his
allegations, including the one about Olympic medal-winners who
have escaped punishment, the USA Today quoted Exum's attorney John
McKendree as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the case, Exum also charged that USOC leaders hampered his
anti-drug battle and denied him promotions and opportunities
because he is black, saying that he was forced to resign and will
be seeking lost pay and benefits in addition to punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
USOC chief executive officer Norm Blake criticized the timing
of the lawsuit, filed less than two months before the start of the
2000 Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia, because it raises "
unwarranted allegations" that tarnish the reputation of American
athletes.
</P>
<P>
Exum resigned June 5 after nine years as director of the USOC's
Drug Control Administration, saying he was forced out by racial
discrimination, ethical dilemmas, harassment and other factors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
