<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Urge Halt to Damage to Ancient Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of Chinese scholars today
urged that the rampant damage being done to ancient cities be
stopped and that officials responsible for such activities be
investigated according to law.
</P>
<P>
The experts from the State Cultural Relics Bureau and other
departments revealed at a seminar on protecting ancient cities
that a number of important historical cities are being seriously
damaged to pave the way for urban construction and infrastructure
building.
</P>
<P>
Among the cities are Anyang in central China's Henan province,
where the capital of the Shang Dynasty was located and the
earliest Chinese characters on animal bones were discovered. The
local government has built a highway that has badly damaged
historical sites.
</P>
<P>
Another is the eastern city of Dinghai, where the first battle
of the Opium War was fought, in 1840. Most of the old buildings
have been pulled down in order to facelift the area, despite local
criticism.
</P>
<P>
The scholars listed a number of other ancient cities that have
been disfigured, including Guiyang, an important city in the
history of the Long March, and Xiangfan, where there was once a 1,
000-year-old wall.
</P>
<P>
Many cities have lost the qualification for bidding for being
listed as World Cultural Heritage because of such destruction,
according to the scholars.
</P>
<P>
To people's astonishment, many officials consider such
destruction to be achievements in promoting economic growth, they
noted.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that the authorities regularly investigate and
re-evaluate the historical cities, and officials responsible for
such damages be punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
