<HEADLINE> Referendum Needed to Approve Agreement With Israel: Palestinian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Public referendum was the sole way for
the Palestinians to accept a possible agreement with Israel,
Mustafa al-Barghuti, member of Palestinian People's Party's (PPP)
General Secretariat, said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Most Palestinian factions were not represented in the ongoing
talks at Camp David between Palestinian leaders Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak under the auspice of United
States President Bill Clinton, he said.
</P>
<P>
Any agreement to be reached at the Camp David summit would not
be accepted by the Palestinians unless it complies with the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) Central Council's decision
on Jerusalem, borders, refugees and settlements, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said referendum was the sole means to learn whether the
possible deal meets the redlines set by the council, the
centralized power body within the Palestine National Council.
</P>
<P>
The 129-member PLO Central Council approved early this month
Arafat's plan to declare an independent state on September 13 this
year with Jerusalem as its capital, even if a peace deal cannot be
reached with Israel by that time.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP)
disengaged itself from the Palestinian delegation to Camp David
talks, objecting what it called U.S. pressures on Arafat to twist
his attitude and interfere in Palestinian internal affairs.PPP and
DFLP are both opposition factions in the PLO.
</P>
<P>
The talks at Camp David, near Washington, entered the eighth day
on Tuesday with no reported breakthrough on the final-status
issues, specially the fate of Jerusalem and refugees.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Israeli side was said to have asked to expand
Israeli control over Jerusalem by annexing Maalita Adumim, Gush
Atsbun and Gibat Zaif Allah Jewish settlement into the disputed
holy city.
</P>
<P>
Israel demanded full Israeli control over those locations while
it proposed handing over some quarters of the city to the
Palestinians and establishing a safe passage to the Temple Mount
and allowing a Palestinian flag on the shrine, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
