<HEADLINE> Estrada Reassures Public on Special Powers Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
reassured the people Tuesday that his bid to seek special powers
from Congress is intended solely to speed up the rehabilitation
and development of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The president told reporters here that the fast-track
implementation of Mindanao projects through these extra powers
will prove to the people of Mindanao his administration's
sincerity and resolve to secure a better future for them.
</P>
<P>
"We have no other intention but to speed up the development of
Mindanao, nothing else," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada asked critics of the government's proposed extra powers
measure to first scrutinize the merits of the proposed bill before
"issuing unsubstantiated comments against it."
</P>
<P>
"We have no other aim but to fast-track Mindanao's development
and put in place confidence building measures to show our Muslim
brothers that we are sincere in developing Mindanao as soon as
possible," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
He said his administration will attack the root cause of the
Muslim in urgency -- which is poverty -- through the
implementation of socio-economic development projects and programs
in the long-neglected island.
</P>
<P>
The measure will include provisions providing for a moratorium
on strike and lockouts, the suspension of temporary restraining
orders involving certain and vital government infrastructure
projects, and the declaration of tax holidays and special economic
zones in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the measure will not allow negotiated contracts
for infrastructure projects and the procurement of supplies. It
will instead push for public biddings, which will ensure
transparency and graft-free contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
