<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Inflation Rate Remains at 5.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The official inflation rate
remained unchanged at 5.1 percent last month, Statistics South
Africa announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bureau head Mark Orkin said the main contributors to the
inflation rate were similar to those in May this year.
</P>
<P>
"These were annual increases in transport -- mainly due to a
23-percent rise in petrol prices over the year -- food, medical
care and health expenses and household operation," Orkin said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
He said these factors were partially offset by the drop in
mortgage interest rates which fell from 19 to 14.5 percent in the
past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The annual percentage change in the CPIX (the consumer price
index), excluding mortgage interest rates, also remained the same
at 8.5 percent in metropolitan areas in June, Orkin said.
</P>
<P>
Food prices rose at the annual rate of 9.5 percent last month,
up from 8.8 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
"This was mainly due to annual increases in the prices of
vegetables, meat and grain products," Orkin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
