<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-East Germany Sports Boss Gets Sentence in Doping Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A Berlin court handed down a
suspended sentence against former East German sports boss Manfred
Ewald on charges of doping the mainly young female athletes who
brought huge swimming and track and field success to the country.
</P>
<P>
Ewald, 74, got a 22-month suspended prison sentence, and co-
defendant Manfred Hoeppner, a former top East German sports doctor,
received an 18-month suspended sentence, according to local media
reporting.
</P>
<P>
The sentences came at the end of a lengthy trial which heard
often emotional accounts from the victims of how they suffered
hair growth, muscle-mass increase and other severe hormonal
dysfunctions.
</P>
<P>
Both officials were found guilty of 20 of an original 142
counts of aiding and abetting bodily harm in connection with the
systematic doping programme, which also resulted in ailments from
liver disease to miscarriages and even death.
</P>
<P>
Both men also were ordered to pay the court costs of 20 women
who joined as co-plaintiffs, all former East German athletes who
say they still suffer the side-effects of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
Ewald said nothing after leaving the court while Hoeppner said,
"I think the court did an orderly job. I can live with the ruling.
"
</P>
<P>
Former track and field athlete Brigitte Michel said the co-
plaintiffs were disappointed with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
"We, the victims, are not satisfied at all. The abuses cannot
be corrected with any ruling," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ewald was president of East Germany's sports federation from
1961-88 and of its National Olympics Committee from 1973 until the
country ceased to exist in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Hoeppner, as the country's top sports doctor, worked out the
details of the doping program _ including the secrecy rules _ and
distributed the steroids to the sports doctors and coaches, the
court found.
</P>
<P>
The results were dramatic: Little East Germany, with less than
17 million people, went from 20 gold medals in 1972 to an
astounding 40 in 1976. East Germans won 11 of 13 events in women's
swimming in 1976 and again in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The court said it handed down a lesser sentence to Hoeppner
because he had apologized to the former athletes and cooperated
with prosecutors in other doping cases. Ewald never made a direct
apology.
</P>
<P>
About 20 former East German coaches, doctors and other have
been convicted and given fines, suspended sentences or both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Melvin Lister Wins Long Jump in U.S. Olympic Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Collegians Melvin Lister,
Dwight Phillips and Walter Davis swept the men's long jump top
three spots at the Olympic track and field trials Monday night,
but will they be good enough to extend the Americans' domination
of the event at the Sydney Games?
</P>
<P>
The United States has won every Olympic long jump competition
since 1964 except for the 1980 Moscow Games boycott.
</P>
<P>
The streak of seven straight gold medals, including the last
four by Carl Lewis and the world record jump by Bob Beamon in 1968,
now appears in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
Lister's best jump of 8.32 meters was the shortest winning
performance at the trials since Larry Myricks' 8.28 meters in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Lister was elated, pumping his fists in the air after he
landed. But his excitement has to be tempered as U.S. long jumping
has deteriorated after Lewis retired in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Only two Americans were ranked in the top 10 last year --
Erick Walder at No. 4 and Roland McGhee at No. 10, and the United
States was shut out of medals at the World Championships. Walder
finished sixth and McGhee seventh Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Phillips was second at 8.14 meters, and Davis finished third
at 8.11 meters.
</P>
<P>
Sandra Glover, an elementary school teacher in Houston until
this year, ran the fastest time in the world this year in winning
the women's 400-meter hurdles in 53.33 seconds, beating world
record-holder Kim Batten and Tonja Buford-Bailey to second and
third in 54.70 and 54.80 seconds respectively.
</P>
<P>
Glover who was to make her first Olympic team, was last year's
U.S. champion and fifth at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Four-time NCAA champion Seilalu Sua won the women's discus at
65.90 meters, the second-longest ever by an American and the
longest in 14 years, only next to Carol Cady's national record of
66.10 meters.
</P>
<P>
Sua set the American junior record three times in 1997 and has
a habit of hitting big throws in championship meets.
</P>
<P>
Suzy Powell finished second at 64.58 and Kristin Kuehl was
third at 61.74.
</P>
<P>
Lynda Blutreich, the American record-holder in the javelin,
won the event at 58.28 meters, and will be the only U.S.
representative at the Olympic games if no one else reaches the "A"
standard by September 11.
</P>
<P>
Blutreich, an assistant coach at Duke, finished third at the
1996 trials, but did not go to Atlanta because she did not meet
the qualifying standard.
</P>
<P>
Kim Kreiner was second at 57.06 and Emily Carlstein third at
56.98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing-Invested Company Starts Construction in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-US company producing
composite material parts for the aviation industry started
construction work today in this north China port city.
</P>
<P>
Three investors, Boeing, US Hexue, and the China Aviation
Industry No.1 Group, shared the total investment of 52 million U.S.
dollars. All the company's raw materials will be imported, and all
its products in the initial period will be sold abroad.
</P>
<P>
The company, located in the Tanggu Maritime New and High-tech
Zone of Tianjin, will be equipped with the most advanced
production and testing equipment, and key engineering and
management staff members will undergo training programs in the U.S.
The quality test standard is to be introduced from Boeing.
</P>
<P>
With registered capital of 20.01 million U.S. dollars, the
first-stage construction site is some 6,000 sq m, and is expected
to go into operation in July 2001. The annual sales volume is
estimated at around 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ken Yata, deputy CEO of Boeing, and Dave Tanonis, CEO of Hexue,
attended today's ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
