</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Hungarian bus manufacturer Ikarus has offered a joint
venture for bus production in Turkey, reported Turkish Daily News
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ikarus Turkey-desk manager Erzebet Loczy said that although
Turkey is an important market, Ikarus cannot sell buses there due
to stiff competition from Asian companies and a major disadvantage
in prices despite good quality.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem can be overcome by producing buses in Turkey
and appealed to the Turkish authorities to support a joint
Hungarian-Turkish Ikarus project.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's first nuclear power plant project will
probably be postponed for a long time amid controversy between the
government and the bidding consortia, reported Turkish Daily News
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Energy and Natural Resources Ministry should select the
winning consortium by July 24, the latest deadline set after
several postponements.
</P>
<P>
However, the announcement is set to be put off for at least
another year due to the Treasury's reluctance to provide guarantees
for the financing of the five billion U.S. dollars plant to be
built in Akkuyu in the southern province of Mersin.
</P>
<P>
But bidders will not accept another delay. A representative of
the U.S. firm Westinghouse warned they will withdraw their bid if
the government again postpones it.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Increasing poverty and the erosion of purchasing power
in Turkey are attracting greater attention as the government's
anti-inflation program puts extraordinary pressure on wages and
farm produce prices, reported Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Unequal income distribution and low growth rates are also shown
as the basic reasons for the fragility of the Turkish economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate there are 20 million poor people, with five
million of them below subsistence level. In other words, there are
five million people in Turkey suffering from hunger.
</P>
<P>
Unfair income distribution and widespread poverty do not only
have economic implications, but also political ramifications.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Finance Minister Avraham Shochat announced
on Monday plans to continue reducing purchase taxes on electrical
appliances. Shochat refused to mention any figures for his promised
reductions or to say which highly-taxed electrical appliances will
be included in his plans.
</P>
<P>
Current purchase taxes range from 30-55 percent on large home
appliances such as refrigerators, washing machines and stoves and
from 65-85 percent on luxury items and home entertainment equipment
such as dishwashers, stereos and video recorders.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Postal Authority has issued a tender
for a computer company to devise a program that will enable it to
sell stamps via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Officials estimate the authority will complete preparations to
sell stamps via an Internet site by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
A program is being developed that will allow customers to
download stamps from the authority's web site after paying for them
via credit card, print them out on a home printer and stick them on
an envelope to put in the mail.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Bank of Israel issued a report on Monday
calling for increasing the minimum wage by adopting standards for
the calculation of such salaries.
</P>
<P>
It noted that over 50 percent of employers surveyed pay their
workers less than the minimum wage, currently 2,798 shekels ( about
700 U.S. dollars). The sum is updated on April 1 each year, based
on 47.5 percent of the average salary.
</P>
<P>
One of the recommendations raised is to automatically link
salaries to the consumer price index, which would maintain their
real value. Another option is to link the minimum wage to the
median salary.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish company, Ezinc Metal Sanayi A.S., which is
based in central Kayseri province, is exporting solar collectors to
European and African countries, reported the Anatolia News Agency
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ezinc Metal Sanayi A.S. Deputy General Director, Hakan Alas,
told reporters Tuesday they have exported 1.3 million U.S. dollars
copper and aluminium solar collectors to Spain, Italy, France,
Netherlands, Switzerland, Austria, Egypt, Libya, Tunisia, Saudi
Arabia, Yemen and Jordan in last six months.
</P>
<P>
Alas said they plan to increase their solar collectors exports
to three million U.S. dollars by the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
