<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Continue Seeking Release of All Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government reassured
the public Tuesday that it would continue to seek the release of
all hostages still being held by the Abu Sayyaf in their lairs in
the southern provinces of Sulu and Basilan.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said the government remains
hopeful the release of German hostage Renate Wallert would be the
beginning of a series of breakthroughs to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this is the start of breakthroughs in the case. We
hope this will cover not just the Malaysian captives but the
Europeans as well," Zamora said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Zamora also stressed the government didn't pay any ransom for
Wallert's release. "We always believe in a no-ransom policy. Any
ransom you give would allow them to buy arms and recruit new men,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf released Wallert Monday but still kept her son
and husband in captivity. Wallert was flown to Manila and has been
brought back to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Wallert as the first European hostage to be released since the
Abu Sayyaf took 21 persons hostage from a resort in Sipadan Island
of Malaysia on April 23.
</P>
<P>
Her release also came days after the foreign ministers of
France, Finland and Germany met with Philippine President Joseph
Estrada over the crisis.
</P>
<P>
On July 14, the Abu Sayyaf released a Malaysian hostage,
bringing to two the Malaysian they had freed.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the hostages abducted from Sipadan Island, the Abu
Sayyaf is also reportedly holding 16 Filipinos, three French
journalists, one German journalist in different places.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado expressed
confidence on Monday that the government can secure the safe
release of all the other hostages soon.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado also reiterated the government's willingness to
discuss community projects with the Abu Sayyaf once the crisis is
over.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier said it would implement community
development projects for Mindanao, acknowledging the need to
address the root of crime and rebellion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
