<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Khmer Rouge Commander Released from Charge of Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 18 (Xinhua)-- A Cambodian court on Tuesday
released a former Khmer Rouge commander who had faced six charges
of attempted murder, kidnapping, robbery, armed group, terrorism
and destruction of state property.
</P>
<P>
Chhouk Rin, 48, military commander in former Khmer Rouge
controlled district in Kampot province, located about 140
kilometers southwest of Phnom Penh, faced the above charges
including a charge of murdering three western backpackers in a
train ambush in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The attacks caused to the deaths of 10 Cambodian passengers on
train and injured three others at the spot while three foreigners
were killed two months later in the same year.
</P>
<P>
The three backpackers known as Australian David Wilson,
Frenchman Jean Michel Braquet and Briton Mark Slater were killed
along with ten other Cambodians.
</P>
<P>
Judge Thong Sam Ol announced no guilty to Chhouk Rin,
explaining that he defected to the society following an appeal by
the government as stated by the law on outlawing the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
After it has brought to force, this law allows an amnesty
period of six months for members of the political or military
organization of the 'Democratic Kampuchea' group to reintegrate,
under the administration of the royal government, into the Kingdom
of Cambodia, without being charged for offenses they committed, he
read Article 5 of the Law.
</P>
<P>
Chhouk Rin, defected to the government on Sept.15, 1994,
bringing along some hundreds of ex-Khmer Rouge forces. And he was
promoted as colonel after joining the government since then.
</P>
<P>
Last year, one of his colleagues, Noun Paet, 52, was sentenced
to life imprisonment on the same case because he did not defect to
the government until his arrest.
</P>
<P>
Three former Khmer Rouge commanders have faced the above six
charges, they are Chhouk Rin, Noun Paet and Sam Bith.
</P>
<P>
The cases of Chhouk Rin and Noun Paet have been cleared while
Sam Bit remained free from the hearing.
</P>
<P>
Phnom Penh's court officials, however, said Sam Bith will be
brought to the trial as well whenever an investigation his case is
completed. He is ranked as a brigadier general, advisor to the
defense ministry.
</P>
<P>
Australian government has urged Cambodian government to take
legal action against Sam Bith.
</P>
<P>
The court has issued an arrest warrant to Sam Bith since early
this year, but the government has failed to carry out its
obligation.
</P>
<P>
Chhouk Rin was arrested in early Jan, this year and put under
detention since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
