<HEADLINE> Cambodia Ends 5 Years of Pre-history Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, JULY 18 (Xinhua)--The Ministry of Culture and Fine
Arts who cooperated with Hawaii University, U.S.A., have completed
its pre-history research in Cambodia's southern and eastern
province.
</P>
<P>
The project has been started since 1995 in a move to research
artifacts from under the ground anywhere in the country during pre-
history, said officials at Culture Ministry on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The pre-history research is very much important to know that
Cambodia keeps a lot of artifacts under the ground," said Princess
Norodom Bupphadevi, Minister of Culture and Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
The princess, meanwhile, said she appealed a cooperation
between Hawaii University and Cambodian University of Fine Arts to
go ahead on their research on pre-Cambodian history in order to
maintain the culture and tradition.
</P>
<P>
Tuy Koeun, director of Fine Arts University, said Hawaii
University has provided financial assistance and 10 experts of
archaeologists to work together with 8 Cambodian archaeologists to
research in some sites in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is the first pre-history research in centuries.
</P>
<P>
During the research, they had found ghost homes with some
archaic jars and other artifacts, said the director of Fine Arts
University.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia is one of the countries in the world which remains
rich in ancient temples. Outstandingly, is Angkor Wat complex.
</P>
</TEXT>
