<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Madame Tussaud's to Open in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Have you ever imagined sharing
the picturesque view of Victoria Harbor with nearly one hundred
most famous celebrities in the world, including famous British
writer Shakespeare, and pop super stars like Michael Jackson and
Madonna?
</P>
<P>
This fantasy will come true when the reputed Madame Tussaud's
studio in London opens its third permanent overseas wax portraits
exhibition, which is also the first in Asia, at the Victoria Peak,
Hong Kong, in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Preparation for Madame Tussaud's Hong Kong is on the full wing
and 94 world celebrities will make their Hong Kong debut as
scheduled, Richard Hollyer, Head of Molding of the Madame Tussaud'
s studio in London, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The heads, arms, bodies and clothes of the wax figures have
arrived in Hong Kong in over 100 crates for assembling and
decoration.
</P>
<P>
At a rented workshop at the Hong Kong's Academy for Performing
Arts, Hollyer and a small team of experts who have specially flown
in from London are working on the wax figures, fitting together
various body parts, dressing them, and most important of all,
doing detailed hair styling and skin coloring, which is key to
make the figures lifelike.
</P>
<P>
Except a few portraits still awaiting a final touch, the
majority of the wax figures have been assembled and transported to
the Peak, including the portraits Hong Kong tycoon Li Ka-shing,
Movie star Jackie Chan, and windsurfing champion Lee Lai Shan.
</P>
<P>
"We sometimes say our attraction is the next best thing to
meeting these celebrities in real life, but in some ways it is
better than the real things," said Peter Carson, general manager
of the Madame Tussaud's Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Where in real life would you have 100 celebrities all gathered
under one roof?" he said.
</P>
<P>
For guests to Madame Tussaud's, they can interact with
incredibly realistic likeness of celebrities, movies stars,
sporting heroes and world leaders, get up close and personal and
even be photographed with them.
</P>
<P>
The original Madame Tussaud's in London, which was founded by
Madame Marie Tussaud, has a 200-year history of modeling
celebrities. Since its founding in 1884, Madame Tussaud's has been
London's most popular attraction and drawn over 2.5 million
visitors yearly.
</P>
<P>
Since Hong Kong is the most popular tourist attraction in the
Asian region, Madame Tussaud's has chosen it as its third
permanent overseas location, the others being in Amsterdam, since
1970, and Las Vegas which opened last July, said Hollyer.
</P>
<P>
Madame Tussaud's Hong Kong will feature a variety of themed
areas including Movie World, Sports and Behind the Scenes, a
creation of the sculptor's studio showing the mysterious procedure
how lifelike wax portraits are made. The new Madame Tussaud's in
Hong Kong is expected to draw up to 500,000 visitors a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
