<HEADLINE> China to Launch Massive Gas Pipeline Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China will start construction of a
703-km-long gas pipeline extending from southwest China's Sichuan
Province to Hubei Province in central China before the end of this
year, according to today's China Petroleum News.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the gas pipeline, expected to be completed
by early 2003, is part of the country's huge project of sending
gas from west to east.
</P>
<P>
The main part of the pipeline starts at Zhongxian County in
Chongqing, the largest metropolis in southwest China, and ends in
Wuhan, capital of Hubei, with an investment totaling 2.9 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that construction of infrastructure and
supporting facilities related to the pipeline project requires a
total investment of 7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Hubei has worked out an initial plan to develop eight chemical
projects by utilizing the gas, with total investment estimated at
17 billion yuan. The gas to be used by the eight chemical projects
is expected to hit 2.75 billion cu m annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
