<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Get More Aid From EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has formally
notified the Lebanese government of its intention to raise its
pledged aid package from 120 million euros (108 million U.S.
dollars) to more than 200 million euros (180 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The aid package was approved at the Washington 1996 Friends of
Lebanon conference for the 1996-2000 period, An Nahar newspaper
Tuesday quoted diplomatic sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used for the implementation of development
projects for the entire country but preferably for the south, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The sources denied reports that some EU members have recently
expressed reservation about giving additional aid to Lebanon, and
stressed that the money will be delivered after the EU completes a
study of the projects which Lebanon plans to implement.
</P>
<P>
The EU has not yet made any decision about the donor conference
for helping reconstruct south Lebanon due to be held in Beirut on
July 27. Its member countries will be present at the meeting at an
ambassadorial level.
</P>
<P>
The EU will make its final decision on the size of the aid at
its September conference of donor states that will be held at
ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
Since signing the Economic and Financial Cooperation Agreement
with the European Community in 1977, Lebanon has benefited from
more than 900 million euros (810 million dollars)in grants, loans
and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
The money went to projects in reconstruction, economic and
social development, human rights, environmental protection and
refugee assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
