<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Speaker Expects Peace Agreement at Camp David </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel could reach a peace
agreement with the Palestinians at the Camp David summit, but the
outcome might not be clear until the last minute, said Israel
Knesset (parliament) Speaker Avraham Burg here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Ehud Barak's mood is very cautious but
determined as the Camp David summit enters its decisive state,"
Burg told local media.
</P>
<P>
"I would say it is the highest motivation I have ever seen in
any Israeli leader to make such a risky breakthrough in order to
bring peace for the people of Israel and the Palestinians," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the prospects for reaching an agreement at the
summit, Burg said he still hoped a deal was possible.
</P>
<P>
"In Israel usually the best solutions come at the last minute...
with the Palestinian side they are coming sometimes even after the
last moment," he added.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which began at Camp David near Washington last
Tuesday and was attended by Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and U.S. President Bill Clinton, is aimed at working out a
framework agreement on key issues such as Jerusalem, borders,
refugees, settlements, ahead of the September 13 target date for a
final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Washington said that the pace of the peace talks at
Camp David had been accelerated on Tuesday due to Clinton's
anticipated departure for Japan to attend the G-8 summit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his advisors are pressing both the Israeli and
Palestinian sides to reach the framework agreement before his
departure on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If an agreement or declaration is not reached, the two sides
could decide to suspend the talk or to continue at Camp David and
wait for Clinton's return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
