<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament to Debate Early Election Bills Again: Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset, or Parliament,
will bring two bills which call for dissolving the Knesset and hold
early elections, to the vote in two weeks, Speaker Avraham Burg
announced Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The move will revive the opposition parties' early election
threats against Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who is now attending a
three-way summit with U.S. and Palestinian leaders at Camp David,
Maryland in order to reach an Israeli-Palestinian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who was elected to his post last July, should end his
four-year term in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The two bills were submitted by the major opposition faction
Likud and another right-wing party Yisrael Beiteinu -- National
Union.
</P>
<P>
Burg announced that he had approved the vote of the two bills,
which will take place before the Knesset's summer recess due to
begin on August 4.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a similar early-election motion, also proposed by
Yisrael Beiteinu -- National Union and Likud, was defeated by the
government in its first reading in the Knesset with the help of the
ultra-Orthodox Shas party.
</P>
<P>
Barak promised more financial budget for Shas's educational
network, in return for the pivotal party's voting against the
early-election bill.
</P>
<P>
It was said then that according to Israeli law, since the bill
was dismissed, the oppositions should wait at least six months
before they could table a similar one asking for early elections,
unless Speaker Burg concluded that a substantive change has
occurred in the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
However, the Shas party, along with two right-wing partners in
Barak's coalition, Yisrael Ba'aliya and National Religious Party
had resigned from the government ahead of the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Legal advisers of the Knesset thus ruled, Burg said Tuesday,
that the bills could be voted upon once again due to the drastic
change of the political scene.
</P>
<P>
Burg said that he had informed the government about his
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
