<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Ordered to Explain Businessman's Presence at Camp David </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli High Court of Justice
on Tuesday instructed Prime Minister Ehud Barak to explain within
five days why Yossi Ginnosar, a businessman, is on behalf of the
government at the three-way Camp David summit in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Under the interim injunction issued by the court, Barak has
to show that there is no conflict of interests between Ginossar's
activities in the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and his
participation in the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Ginossar has been Barak's personal liaison with PNA Chairman
Yasser Arafat. He is now doing public relations work for Barak in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The court's instruction followed a petition by Knesset
(Parliament) Member Zvi Hendel from the National Union Party who
demanded that Ginossar not be allowed as a member of the peace
talks delegation.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks ago, Hendel petitioned the High Court to order
Barak to stop using Ginossar as a liaison with Arafat, because he
allegedly maintained highly lucrative business relations with the
PNA.
</P>
<P>
In response to Hendel's charges, the Prime Minister's office
issued a statement saying that "the prime minster invited Ginossar
to the talks because of the contribution he has made to several
prime ministers in the past in developing relations with the
Palestinians and his good connections. All three parties to the
talks are pleased that he is there."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barak instructed David Ivry, Israel's ambassador to
Washington, to continue assisting three Israeli public relations
experts who are using the Israeli Embassy as their base to explain
the government's stance in peace talks. They are businessmen Tal
Silberstein, Moshe Gaon, and Yoni Koren.
</P>
<P>
Barak's instruction was given only a few hours after Ivry
decided to suspend the activities of the lecturers. Ivry's decision
was made in light of two petitions submitted to the Israeli High
Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
The petitions were submitted by the opposition Likud bloc and by
the right-wing group "Betzedek." They requested that the High Court
of Justice immediately instruct the prime minister, his legal
advisor and the Civil Service Commissioner to prevent private
citizens from filling official positions.
</P>
<P>
The Camp David summit between Barak, Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton began on July 11 in a bid to hammer out a
framework deal for the settlement of the final status issues
between the Israelis and Palestinians, including the status of
Jerusalem, border, water resources, the future of Jewish
settlements and the Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
As the talks entered the crucial stage, the opposition parties
in Israel also stepped up their efforts to undermine Barak's
political authority in the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
