<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tamil Rebels Suffer Heavy Casualties in Recent Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's separatist Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels has suffered heavy casualties
in recent fighting, a government statement said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The LTTE had admitted that 943 tiger cadres were killed
between April 1 and July 15, 2000," said the statement issued by
the government's Special Media Information Center, adding that
majority of those killed were from the eastern Batticaloa region.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the dead consisted of 13 LTTE's self-styled
lieutenant colonels and 260 other ranking rebels.
</P>
<P>
It said the LTTE has been compelled to enlist elderly civilians
for military training and subsequent deployment. Fifty three of
them have also been killed during the recent confrontations with
the security forces in Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting for a separate homeland called Eelam
in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983, have engaged in weeks of
ferocious assault until May in a bid to retake their former
stronghold of the northern Jaffna peninsula. The government has
rushed thousands of reinforcements and new weapons to Jaffna and
halted the rebel onslaught. 
</P>
</TEXT>
