<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 143 Foreigners Jailed in Malaysia for Breaking Immigration Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A Magistrate's Court in
Malaysia Tuesday charged 143 foreigners for defying immigration
laws.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners, 71 Indonesians, 37 Bangladeshis and 35
Cambodians were charged in the Magistrate's Court in Klang, some
33 kilometers west from here, according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 132 were charged for illegal entry, 10 for overstaying
and one for breaching work permit conditions.
</P>
<P>
They all pleaded guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
Magistrate Mat Ghani Abdullah sentenced those who entered the
country illegally to six months' jail, those for overstayers five
months and for the lone foreigner who violated conditions in his
work permit three months.
</P>
<P>
They will serve their sentences at a detention center before
being deported.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners, 76 men and 67 women, were caught while working
at a wood industry factory in Klang by an Immigration raiding
party on June 29.
</P>
<P>
Their employer and three sub-contractors were also detained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
