<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Journalists Demand Home Minister's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Journalists angry at the
killing of one of their senior colleagues in the western frontier
Jessore town Tuesday asked Home Minister Mohammad Nasim to resign
immediately for failing to give security to them.
</P>
<P>
"Resign today since you have failed to give security to
journalists even at their work places," Gias Kamal Chowdhury, a
senior journalist leader made the demand at a rally of journalists
who gathered at the National Press Club in the city center.
</P>
<P>
Shamsur Rahman, a Special Correspondent of Bengali newspaper
the Janakantha ( the People's Voice) was shot dead at his office
in Jessore town, 273 kilometers west of Dhaka, on Sunday night
while he was writing a report on crime situation in southern
districts. Three armed men walked into his office and shot Rahman,
45, at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
The rally was addressed by leaders of Bangladesh Federal Union
of Journalists (BFUJ) and Dhaka Union of Journalists and editors
of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Iqbal Sobhan Chowdhury, editor of the Bangladesh Observer and
former president of BFUJ, said the terrorists threw a challenge
toward the journalist community killing Rahman. "Unless the
journalists are united, their independence cannot be protected,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The leaders announced a week-long countrywide mourning for
Rahman. The journalists will wear black badges, hold three-hour
work stoppage, hold a rally and processions on Saturday. A
memorandum will be handed over to Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
protesting the killing.
</P>
<P>
Angry journalists across the country protested the terrorist
act Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Overseas Correspondents Association, Bangladesh (OCAB)
Tuesday expressed deep concern at the killing of Rahman.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, OCAB President Farid Hossain said such killings
were a matter of great concern and threat to the freedom of the
press. "Journalists should have safeguards to write the truth,"
the OCAB leader said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Home Minister Mohammad Nasim has gone to Jessore to
guide police in the search for the killers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
