<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Help Drought-hit Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has agreed to
help Iran cope with a severe drought that has hit the country and
inflicted heavy damages, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Jazayeri, secretary of Iran's national committee for
lessening effects of natural disasters, signed an agreement here
Monday with visiting representative of the U.N. Development Program
Francisco Bastali to the effect, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iranian and U.N. experts will cooperate in
forging medium- and long-term projects aimed at countering droughts
and reducing the financial damages.
</P>
<P>
They will also endeavor to formulate appropriate guidelines for
the optimal use of water and related resources.
</P>
<P>
Jazayeri said that drought has so far engulfed 17 Iranian
provinces completely and 11 others partially, resulting in over 13,
181 billion rials (about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in damages to
agricultural, cattle and potable water sectors.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government has allocated some 0.3 percent of
the state budget, equal to 2,600 billion rials (some 317 million
dollars), to combat the drought.
</P>
<P>
Violent protests broke out recently in the southwestern Iranian
city of Abadan over the lack of potable water. Protesters smashed
shop windows and set tires ablaze to vent their anger with the
local government for failing to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been undergoing a particularly dry summer this year
that has worsened the drought problem the country has been facing
since last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
