<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Withdraws International Staff From Southern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has withdrawn
its international observers from southern Iraq, U.N. spokesman in
Iraq George Sommerwill told Xinhua on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sommerwill said that the U.N. began the operation on Sunday by
pulling out its staff from Basra, Misan, Thi-Qar and Qadissiyah in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, Iraqi staffers in the U.N. team are
continuing their work in the above-mentioned provinces.
</P>
<P>
"For the coming week, there will be no international U.N.
observers in southern Iraq," said Sommerwill.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. took the move by listening to "some advice," but the
international observers are expected to be back in the south to
resume their work soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also rule out the possibility that the U.N. activities in
Iraq might be affected by the event.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between Iraq and the U.N. has shown signs of
deterioration recently.
</P>
<P>
An editorial, issued by an English-language newspaper Monday on
the 32nd anniversary of the revolution on July 17, 1968, condemned
the U.N. for doing nothing to Iraq and the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"All Iraqis and fair-minded people of the world feel that the U.
N., in one way or another, is the main reason behind prolonging
sanctions imposed on Iraq," the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan vehemently attacked the
U.N. Security Council on Sunday, claiming that it has turned into a
council "for war against the Third World states, especially those
rejecting the U.S. subordination and submission."
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-Iraqi relations were also affected by the killing of
two staffers of the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) in
late June.
</P>
<P>
A lone gunman, identified as 38-year-old Fuad Haidar, burst into
the FAO building on June 28, killing two FAO staffers. After a two-
hour confrontation with the Iraqi security forces, the gunman
turned himself in.
</P>
<P>
Haidar said that he did this in protest against the decade-old
U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said that the sanctions have so far claimed the lives
of over 1.3 million people, most of them children and the elderly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
