<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Traditional Exports Down 8.7 Percent Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's traditional
exports decreased by 8.7 percent in 1999 compared with the
previous year due to a decline in production volume and world
market price.
</P>
<P>
A Bank of Tanzania Economic Bulletin released here on Monday
said traditional exports declined from 167.5 million U.S. dollars
in the fourth quarter of 1998 to 152.9 million dollars in the last
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The document attributed the fall to a decline in export volumes
as well as export unit prices of the export commodities.
</P>
<P>
Export volumes for coffee, cotton, tobacco and cashew nuts went
down by 16.4 percent, 2.5 percent, 7.4 percent and 36.1 percent
respectively when compared with the volumes recorded during the
same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Only sisal and tea recorded an increase in export volumes by 45.
3 percent and 26.6 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Except for cashew nuts, whose export unit price increased by 66.
9 percent, all other traditional exports recorded a decline in
export unit prices when compared with prices attained during the
corresponding period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The fall in export unit prices for most of the traditional
commodities is partly explained by an increase in global
production that left prices depressed, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the fall in demand of commodities in their raw
form and the decline in quality of some traditional commodities
also accounted for unfavorable price movements in the world market.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank report said, unlike traditional
exports, non-traditional exports recorded an increase of 13.2
percent to 94.3 million dollars from 83.3 million dollars recorded
in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The increase was mainly attributed to petroleum products and
mineral exports, which registered sharp increases of 1,072.3
percent and 336.8 percent, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
