<HEADLINE> U.S. Famine Relief Food Arrives in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A consignment of 20,000 tons of
maize donated by the U.S. government to help alleviate hunger in
Kenya has arrived in the Indian Ocean port city of Mombasa in the
southeastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Daily Nation newspaper quoted the World Food Program
(WFP) as saying on Monday that the donation will be distributed to
hungry families in the North Eastern, Rift Valley, Eastern and
Coast provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Already more than 14,000 tons of the relief food has been
discharged and is on the way to the targeted destinations," said
Joern Lose, WFP official at Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The official said the maize consignment, which is worth over 5
million U.S. dollars, was donated by the U.S. Agency for
International Development.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 3 million Kenyans are in
desperate need of food assistance this year compared to 961,000 in
1992 when the country experienced severe drought last time.
</P>
<P>
According to the Office of the President, the Kenyan government
has purchased 868,680 bags of maize (90 kilograms per bag) during
the last season, of which 811,600 bags have been distributed to
drought- and famine-hit areas since July last year.
</P>
<P>
In mid-June, the government announced to waiver the duty of
imported maize to encourage local millers to import more maize as
the government's famine relief stocks had dwindled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government set aside 500 million shillings (
about 6.5 million dollars) for the purchase of some 303,000 bags
of maize for distribution to food deficient districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
