<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-tailers in U.S. Hit by Internet Fraud: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Fraud on the Internet is
taking its toll on electronic retailers (e-tailers) in the United
States, who are also getting hit by credit card companies,
according to a survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey of some 160 U.S. companies, conducted by research
and consulting firm Gartner, reveals that 12 times more fraud
exists on Internet transactions than offline ones, and that e-
tailers are paying credit card discount that are 66 percent higher
than traditional retailer fee.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Gartner said, Web merchants bear the liability and
costs in cases of fraud, while credit companies generally absorb
the fraud for traditional retailers as long as the retailer
follows procedures and saves a physical signature on a credit card
transaction receipt.
</P>
<P>
Surveyed e-tailers reported that their average credit card
discount rate was 2.5 percent plus about 30 cents a transaction.
The same average for traditional retailers is about 1.5 percent
plus 30 cents a transaction. This means a merchant may pay credit
card processors 2.8 U.S. dollars for selling a shirt online, but
pay only 1.8 dollars for the same transaction in the physical
store.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, e-tailers must pay for Internet payment gateways
and fraud detection, which can add another 50 cents to each
transaction. Meanwhile, credit card companies have failed to offer
e-tailers cost-effective solution for fraud prevention.
</P>
<P>
According to Gartner, there is no incentive for a credit card
company to break this unfair fee structure for e-tailers. But the
credit card issuer that is bold enough to lower the fees online
could create a real competitive advantage on the Web and possibly
gain early market share among e-tailers and Internet shoppers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
