<HEADLINE> WTO Technical Assistance Fund Gets Donation From Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch government has pledged 2.
6 million Dutch guilders (about 1.2 million U.S. dollars) for the
period 2000-2001 to the Global Trust Fund for World Trade
Organization (WTO) Technical Assistance to benefit developing
countries and economies in transition.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Netherlands' Ministry for Economic Affairs,
Director-General for Foreign Economic Relations Dirk Bruinsma on
Monday signed a memorandum of understanding with WTO Director-
General Mike Moore, according to a WTO press release.
</P>
<P>
"Funding technical assistance to help developing countries
implement their WTO obligations is in all WTO members' interest
and no charity," said Bruinsma.
</P>
<P>
"Technical assistance is certainly not the only solution to
implementation problems but the least we can do is provide a
minimum and stable source of funding."
</P>
<P>
Moore said: "Once again, I am extremely grateful to the
Netherlands for its donation to the Trust Fund. Only through these
types of generous contributions can the WTO respond now to an
increasing demand for technical assistance."
</P>
<P>
He said his organization's regular budget for technical
assistance of about 450,000 U.S. dollars is insufficient.
</P>
<P>
Moore has called on WTO members to raise the regular budget for
technical assistance. A group of countries, including the
Netherlands, have proposed a phased increase in the regular budget
of 10 million Swiss francs (about 6.6 million U.S. dollars)
earmarked for technical assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
