<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Selling Snakes, Scorpions on Internet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Snakes, scorpions and toads are
raised at Wang Lizhong's breeding center, where requests for his
considerable stock of all that slithers and hops are arriving from
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Every day, the 32-year-old farmer in east China's Zhejiang
Province, has a packed schedule of meeting clients, taking calls,
and returning e-mails. Only months ago, Wang was a man without a
market, but now, he says, orders for his critters are "pouring in
like snowflakes."
</P>
<P>
Last March, a Japanese company bought three tons of sun-dried
snakes for medicinal purposes from Wang's website.
</P>
<P>
"I had no idea the Internet was so magical," said the excited
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
In less than two years, Wang has signed 1.3 million yuan (about
157,000 U.S. dollars) worth of deals, earning 600,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Only few years ago, he lived in a village in the city of
Haining, and knew nothing about computers or the Internet. But he
learned from a friend who opened a computer shop in a nearby town.
</P>
<P>
In September 1998, Wang opened his website, hetianlong.com, for
just 2,000 yuan (about 240 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
From that point on, he said, "customers have been like pies
falling from the sky." His products are sold to Guangdong, Fujian,
Henan and other provinces in China, as well as Japan, the Republic
of Korea and other counties.
</P>
<P>
China has 13 million Internet users, 200,000 of which are in
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
