<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Selling Snakes, Scorpions on Internet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Other villagers in Zhejiang are cashing in on the e-commerce
craze. From his site alibaba.com, Lin Haibo earns more than 20,000
yuan a month selling fashionable shoes to the Republic of Korea
and as far away as the United States.
</P>
<P>
More and more Chinese peasants are learning computer skills to
handle business instead of trekking long distances to meet clients
in person.
</P>
<P>
Another farmer who sells shoes via the Internet is Wang Yong'an,
in Yuexi county in the Dabie Mountain, Anhui Province in east
China.
</P>
<P>
For centuries, the rugged mountain roads made it difficult for
peasants to climb out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Wang opened a website to sell handtailored cloth shoes.
To cater to international clients, he often went to study English
at a school more than 10 kilometers away and learned computer
science on his own by reading texts on the subject.
</P>
<P>
Wang has helped more than 1,000 families escape poverty by
selling shoes made by them to customers in the United States,
Japan, Britain and Finland.
</P>
<P>
This year, he opened a new website yangsheng.com in Chinese and
English languages, and his ambitious goal is to help more than 4,
000 families in the mountainous areas earn more money.
</P>
<P>
"Internet shortened the distance between this mountainous area
and the global market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zongkang, a farmer in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, sells ginger and sugar cane to other parts of
China and foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Grape lovers can log on to turpan.com.cn to order produce from
farmers in Turpan, the world's lowest basin, in northwest China's
Xinjiang Autonomous Region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
