<HEADLINE> ICBC Completes Acquisition of HK Union Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial and Commercial Bank
of China (ICBC) announced here today that it has finished all
legal procedures for acquiring the Hong Kong Union Bank and now is
officially the Union Bank's holding company.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a Chinese commercial bank has acquired a
bank listed in the international financial center.
</P>
<P>
ICBC sources said the acquisition has been approved by the
People's Bank of China, the China Securities Regulatory Commission,
the State Administration of Foreign Exchange, the Hong Kong
Monetary Administration and the Hong Kong Securities Regulatory
Commission.
</P>
<P>
On April 19, the ICBC and Hong Kong Merchants (Holding) Co.
signed a trade deal in Hong Kong on acquiring 240 million shares,
or 53.24 percent of Union Bank's total equity, by the ICBC at 7.52
HK dollars per share.
</P>
<P>
Market response to the deal has been positive, with the price
of Union Bank shares rising to 8.7 HK dollars by July 14 when the
deal was completed.
</P>
<P>
The Union Bank maintains its status as a listed company after
the acquisition due to the fact that minority shareholders still
hold up to 30 percent of the bank's equity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
