<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50,000 Tons of Grape May be Dumped in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- About 50,000 to 60,000 tons of
grapes
might end up in dumps in Cyprus this year because of overproduction
and stiff competition in the European market, local media reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The grim prospect was disclosed by Cyprus' Commerce and Industry

Minister Nicos Rolandis.
</P>
<P>
It is very difficult to sell the large quantities of grape to
the wine industry because of its inability to export bottled wine
to the
European market, Rolandis said Monday, after a meeting with
representatives of farmers' unions.
</P>
<P>
The unions stressed the importance of the government support for
the grape production and wine industry.
</P>
<P>
Union leader Michalis Litras said that the solution of dumping
grapes is painful, but it comes out of necessity, adding that the
state is the natural employer of farmers and therefore must bear
the weight of overproduction on its shoulders.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 11,625 tons of grapes had to be dumped for the first
time since 1989, just over 10 percent of a 107,000-ton harvest.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy might be repeated this year, and market conditions
are worse than last year, said reports. Prices on the European
market, for white grapes in particular, are too low this year for
Cyprus' producers to compete.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of Cyprus grapes are exported in raw form or
processed, usually as wine.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government used to buying up producers' unsold grapes
and dispose of them in a bid to keep market prices stable, but it
placed a huge burden on already depleted state coffers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
