<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Charged With Abuse of Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Minister for Water
Resources Kipng'eno arap Ng'eny has been charged with abuse of
office for a loss of about 186 million shillings ( about 2.5
million U.S. dollars) in his position as head of Kenya's former
sole telecommunications corporation.
</P>
<P>
It was one of the biggest cases in the past 20 yeas regarding
the volume of loss caused by abuse of office, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After a claim about his mismanagement was made by Parliament's
Public Accounts Committee, the Kenya Anti-corruption Authority
last week obtained the approval to apprehend him.
</P>
<P>
Ng'eny denied the charge before a Nairobi court on Monday and
was released on 10 million shillings (about 130,000 dollars)
personal bond.
</P>
<P>
The case is expected to be heard again on July 31.
</P>
<P>
The offense was allegedly committed in October 1992 when Ng'eny
was managing director of the defunct Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
