<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo, Nikkei Closes Below 17,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Tuesday on worries that the liquidation of bad loans in Japan may
not go smoothly, with the benchmark Nikkei index closing below 17,
000 points for the first time in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 341.76 points, or 1.98
percent, from Monday's close to end at 16,945.07.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, declined 34.09 points, or 2.16 percent, to 1,
541.95.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 694.26 million
shares from Monday's 604.29 million shares.
</P>
<P>
While market players did not see significant negative factors
to lead share prices sharply lower, uncertainty over corporate
reconstruction, stirred by the failure of department store chain
operator Sogo Co., has made investors reluctant to buy stocks, a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector fell 2.69 percent while wire and cable
makers, which have been drawing active buying, turned downward.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information and technology issues were also lower
despite stability in New York's Nasdaq composite index, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
The mining, nonferrous metal and brokerage sectors marked sharp
declines, while the oil and electric power and gas industries were
the only gainers in 33 business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far exceeded
gainers 1,110 to 221, with 70 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
