<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Government Angered by Campaign Against British Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government blamed some
parliamentarians for making public the delicate dispute over ending
British army exercises off its sovereign bases in Cyprus, local
media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Marios Matsakis, deputy of Democratic Party, faxed
a letter to Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides, demanding the end
of British army exercises outside the bases.
</P>
<P>
The letter, signed by nine deputies, three of them from ruling
Democratic Rally party, five from the main opposition AKEL party
and one from Democratic Party, was subsequently leaked to the
press.
</P>
<P>
The deputies, all from Limassol district, southern coast of the
island, where one of the two British sovereign bases situates,
urged the foreign minister to take measures to terminate as soon as
possible the exercises undertaken by British soldiers outside the
boundaries of their bases.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government, however, has denounced the letter as
mishandling a delicate matter.
</P>
<P>
"In my view, it should not be dealt with by publishing letters.
Any ideas or opinions should be discussed in private by the
government and the foreign ministry before making them public,"
said government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides, Democratic Rally leader Nicos Anastassiades and the
Attorney-general Alecos Markides were thought to have been angered
by the leak, said the report.
</P>
<P>
But Matsakis hit back. slamming the government's reluctance to
confront the British bases.
</P>
<P>
British has retained two sovereign military bases under the 1960
Treaty of Establishment of the Cyprus Republic, one in Limassol
area, and one in southeastern area of the island.
</P>
<P>
The British bases are allowed, under the 1960 treaty, to use
land outside the bases for military exercises for a certain period
each year.
</P>
<P>
Local people believe that the British troops violated the human
rights of Greek Cypriots by holding the military exercises outside
the bases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
