<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt is concerned that an Israel at peace with its Arab
neighbors may compete with it for regional hegemony, and as a
result is unlikely to warm its chilly relations with Israel, even
if a peace agreement is signed with the Palestinians, a political
source in Jerusalem said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The source was explaining the meaning of a cable recently sent
by Israeli Ambassador to Egypt Zvi Mazel, saying that Egypt is not
interested in a normalization of ties, but a continuation of the
present "cold peace," even if Israel inked an agreement with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian Ambassador to Israel Mohanmmed Bassiouny said that
Egypt is not interested in cooling the ties with Israel and the
peace process remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has warned that without an
agreement that would guarantee Palestinian control over Al-Aqsa
Mosque and the Church of the Holy Sepulchre in East Jerusalem,
there would be no deal on any subject at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
The tone of the Palestinian leader's message is indicative of
the general atmosphere at Camp David: The talks are intensive and
there is a rush to meet a deadline that is marked by the departure
of U.S. President Bill Clinton for the G-8 meeting on the Japanese
island of Okinawa on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation believes that the Americans are about to
present a document of bridging proposals in order to push the two
sides toward an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Germany Monday signed a historic deal to pay out DM 10
billion (about 4.8 billion U.S. dollars) to compensate nearly 1
million surviving Nazi-era slave and forced laborers, essentially
closing its reparations programs.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after 18 months of negotiations among
the German government and industry, the U.S., Poland, Russia,
Ukraine, Belarus, the Czech Republic, the Claims Conference, and
Israel, as well as lawyers for Nazi victims who had sued German
industry in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
Slave laborers, who were primarily Jewish Nazi victims, are
expected to receive payments of up to DM 15,000 (about 7,190
dollars). Forced laborers, who are Central and Eastern Europeans,
will receive about DM 5,000 (about 2,397 dollars). Payments could
begin by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Bashar al-Assad, the son of the late Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad, was officially sworn in as the new president of Syria
Monday. The 34-year-old Bashar will begin his seven-year term as
president Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the office-taking ceremony in the parliament in
Damascus, Bashar made his maiden speech, in which he laid his plans
for Syrian policy for the coming year. Most of his address was
devoted to internal Syrian affairs, but toward the end, he
mentioned peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Bashar underscored that Syria would not compromise on the matter
of sovereign Syrian territory and demanded that Israel completely
withdraw from the Golan Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
