<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Venture Capital Investment Hits Record High in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A total of 735 million U.S.
dollars were invested in 129 Israeli hi-tech companies during the
second quarter of the year, setting a new record high in a single
quarter, the Ha'aretz daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The investment eclipsed by 19 percent the previous record of 617
million dollars set in the first quarter, the paper quoted a report
issued on Monday by Kesselman and Kesselman, a local affiliate of
Price Waterhouse Coopers, in Tel Aviv, as saying.
</P>
<P>
It also brought to 1.35 billion dollars the amount of venture
capital raised by local start-ups in the first half of the year,
which is 34 percent more than all of 1999's venture capital
investment.
</P>
<P>
Of the 735 million dollars, 226 million dollars were invested by
62 venture capital funds (57 based here and five in the United
States), and the rest by other venture capital companies, including
institutional and individual investors.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Fellus, head of the hi-tech division of Kesselman and
Kesselman, said that "The steep plunges experienced by dot.com and
technology stocks on Nasdaq last quarter have neither curbed nor
slowed the growth rate of venture capital investment in Israel."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he said, venture capital companies invested
397 million dollars in Internet-related companies this quarter or
54 percent of the total investment, as opposed to 71 percent in the
previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that there has been a recorded drop in
investment in Internet-related companies since 1998, although these
companies still managed to attract the lion's share of venture
capital investment," Fellus was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 129 transactions, also a record high, showed an increasing
trend of venture capital investments in earlier stages. The number
of seed-stage and first-round investments accounted for 50 percent
of all investments in the quarter, up by 55 percent and 42 percent
respectively over the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The report concludes that an increasing number of funds are
finding it necessary to adjust to the reality of earlier stage
investment, as more and newer venture capital firms are beginning
to specialize in this investment field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
