<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Experts Find Link Between Worms Treatment and AIDS Therapy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- There is a connection between
treatment for intestinal worms and level reducing of HIV virus in
the blood of AIDS patients, Israeli medical experts said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The worms do harm to human beings' immune system, thus help the
AIDS virus to do evil, according to Professor Zvi Bentwich, chief
researcher of Kaplan Hospital in Rehovot.
</P>
<P>
When the worms are killed, Bentwich said, the immune system will
be reactivated to fight against the fatal AIDS virus and reduce the
virus level in the blood.
</P>
<P>
The expert said the discovery is very important and his team is
the first in the world to establish such a connection.
</P>
<P>
"I was surprised to find that we are the first but it is the
fact," he said.
</P>
<P>
The findings, which were made in cooperation with Ethiopian
scientists in a five-year research, have been presented to the
recently-concluded world conference on AIDS in South Africa and
aroused great interest from participants, said Bentwich.
</P>
<P>
The discovery has wide implications because the level reducing
of HIV virus can not only slow the AIDS development and extend the
patients' lifecycle, but also reduce their infective ability
through sexual or mother-baby channels.
</P>
<P>
Bentwich said his team will expand its clinical trials in other
African and Asian countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
