<HEADLINE> Uganda, Sudan in Secret Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Government officials from Uganda
and Sudan are reportedly in the United States for talks aimed at
settling differences obstructing the normalization of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which were described as "secret" by a Sudanese
newspaper al-Sahafa, were scheduled to start on Monday under the
auspices of former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, the New Vision
daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Army Spokesman Phinehas Katirima, however, dismissed the
reports in a telephone interview with Xinhua, saying "we are not
of the meeting."
</P>
<P>
He said while Uganda had fulfilled its obligation under the
Nairobi peace agreement to release Sudanese prisoners of war,
Sudan had not done so.
</P>
<P>
Sudan was supposed to facilitate the release of children
abducted by Joseph Kony's Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) rebels, he
said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Sudanese State Minister for Foreign
Relations Ali Abdel Rahman al-Nimeiri headed a government
delegation and left for the talks on Sunday. Meanwhile, Ugandan
State Minister for Regional Cooperation was also reportedly out of
the country, but it was not confirmed whether he was in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese President Omar Hassan al-Bashir and his Ugandan
counterpart Yoweri Museveni signed an agreement in Nairobi last
December to promote normalization of ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The accord aimed to stop either country from supporting rebel
activities in the other and to secure the return of each other's
missing nationals.
</P>
<P>
The LRA has received sanctuary inside Sudan since 1988, while
Uganda has supported the Sudan People's Liberation Army, a rebel
group fighting the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
