<HEADLINE> COMESA to Look Into Taxation Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is to embark on a major taxation policy
study among the 21 member states to identify areas of internal
tariffs harmonization, the Times of Zambia newspaper reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The study, whose terms of reference have already been drawn up,
will start as soon as donor funding is sourced, said the regional
grouping's Director of Trade, Customs and Monetary Affairs
Charles Chanthunya in an interview here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the study would look into differences in tax policies
and practices of particular member states and help the secretariat
to identify areas which require harmonization.
</P>
<P>
Proposals would be made after the study and then a common stand
would be taken, he said, noting that the study is especially
important in the face of the COMESA Free Trade Area to be put in
place by October this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Chanthunya, the external tariffs harmonization
among member states, which started in 1994, is progressing very
well.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that there would be required adjustments made
well before the year 2004 when the exercise is expected to be
finalized.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that by the year 2004, all member states would have
made the necessary adjustments and be able to charge the same
tariffs on goods entering each other's country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
