<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Percent Foreign Stake to Be Allowed in Oman's Industrial Units  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 18 (xinhua) -- Oman is set to boost foreign
ownership of industrial businesses by allowing foreign shares in
projects to rise from the current level of 49 percent to 100
percent, an Omani trade ministry spokesman has said.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign participation in projects that contribute to the
development of the national economy can be lifted to 100 percent,
on condition that the capital is not less than 500 million rials
(1.3 billion U.S. dollars)," Tuesday's Dubai-based daily "Gulf
News" quoted Rashed bin Salem Al-Masruri as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Al-Masruri, the move aim "to stimulate foreign
investment in the industrial sector."
</P>
<P>
In addition, other steps such as "exemption from custom duties
on equipment and essential material for factories for a period of
up to five years with a possible 10-year renewal" were also taken
by the government which is encouraging foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking for investments that benefit the national
economy, especially in the creation of jobs for the local workforce
and in diversifying the (country's) source of revenue," Al-Masruri
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
