<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Surplus Jumps in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Trade surplus of the Philippines
amounted to 1.365 billion U.S. dollars for the first five months
of 2000, which was a 173 percent jump from 500 million dollars a
year ago, the National Statistics Office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Data from the office also showed that total trade in goods for
January to May 2000 stood at 27.047 billion dollars which was 6.5
percent higher than 25.391 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Payments for merchandise imports rose by 3.2 percent to 12.841
billion dollars from 12.445 billion dollars in the same period of
1999.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, exports posted a 9.7 percent increase with
an aggregate revenue of 14.206 billion dollars, up from 12.945
billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
For May alone, merchandise trade grew by 1.7 percent to 5.368
billion dollars from 5.280 billion dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Exports receipts amounted to 2.931 billion dollars in May,
increasing by 6.7 percent from 2.747 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
However, import expenditures declined by 3.8 percent to 2.437
billion dollars in May from 2.533 billion dollars in the same
month of 1999. Trade surplus for the month stood at 494 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan shipped 17.1 percent of the total May 2000 imports
despite a drop of 11.2 percent to 416.71 million dollars from 469.
23 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the second with a 16.9 percent share,
reporting shipments of 412.07 million dollars to the country in
May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
