<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Boosts Exports of Art, Handicraft Articles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam earned 143 million U.S.
dollars from exports of fine art and handicraft articles in the
first six months of this year, an 88.2 percent year-on-year
increase, Vietnam News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fine art and handicraft articles of the country have been
exported to 50 countries and regions, including Singapore and
Japan with about 60 million U.S. dollars worth of house utensils
and ceramics being shipped to Japan annually. As a result,
handicrafts have become one of Vietnam's 10 biggest hard currency
earners.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's export value of handicrafts reached 170 million U.S.
dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has great potential for development of handicraft
production. The Vietnamese government has recently listed
handicrafts among industries enjoying priority. Prime Minister
Phan Van Khai has asked localities and relevant agencies to map
out plans to exploit available materials in accordance with local
socio-economic development plans and to set up a number of
commercial centers at home and abroad with the aim of supporting
sales of fine art and handicraft articles.
</P>
<P>
The country is expected to attain an export value of 250
million U.S. dollars from these products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
