<HEADLINE> Fiji's New President Names Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Within hours of his swearing-in, the new president announced a
government which excluded rebel supporters in key cabinet
positions and named an ethnic Indian to a junior ministerial post,
the website said.
</P>
<P>
Iloilo said several Indian community leaders had been
approached to join the government but had declined.
</P>
<P>
Qarase, an indigenous Fijian, had been named interim prime
minister by Fiji's military, but the rebels accused him of being
too accommodating towards Fiji's ethnic Indian minority.
</P>
<P>
"As head of state and a symbol of national unity in Fiji, I
cannot appoint a cabinet that is expressly committed to excluding
a particular community," Iloilo said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But rebel spokesman Joe Nata rejected Qarase's appointment,
saying: "We are not accepting it."
</P>
<P>
The rebels had made the dismissal of Qarase's interim
government a condition for the release last week of hostages
including deposed ethnic Indian Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
Iloilo earlier called for racial harmony at the swearing-in
ceremony in the capital Suva on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are one country and one people. Everyone deserves to be
shown equal concern and equal consideration," Iloilo said.
</P>
<P>
"Out of the many multi-ethnic and multicultural groups who
have made Fiji their home, and Fiji is a common home, we are one
as one nation and one people," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
