<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Funds to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The board of the World Bank has
approved the release of substantial funds to Kenya as part of the
planned renewed assistance, the East African Standard newspaper
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The funds would help Kenya implement the ongoing public sector
reforms and the poverty reduction strategy as set out in the
interim Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper, said Ramphele Maphele, a
director of the bank and managing director of Human Development,
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, Maphele did not disclose how much the board had
approved for disbursement, only saying that the money is available
and will be released as soon as the necessary formalities
finalized.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi and Head of
Public Service Richard Leakey on Monday, Maphele said the approval
was hastened by the numerous problems now facing Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to Kenyan Finance Minister Chris Okemo, Kenya cleared
the last hurdle in May towards gaining up to 360 million U.S.
dollars from the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (
IMF) as new loans.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts from the World Bank and the IMF were
satisfied with the government's economic recovery programs and
policy measures, he said, adding that the handing out of the money
is likely to begin after July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
