<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls to Help Ease Zambia's Refugees Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has appealed to
the donor community to help ease the pressure on the Zambian
government following the fresh influx of refugees, the Times of
Zambia newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. resident representative Olubanke King-Akerele was quoted as
saying here on Monday during the opening of the 12th Consultative
Group (CG) meeting that the Zambian authorities are under pressure
to look after refugees fleeing from the war-torn countries.
</P>
<P>
She cited the recent arrival of 25,000 Angolan refugees in the
western part of Zambia, saying the situation is compounded by
instability and volatile military position along the Zambian-
Angola border where 9,000 Zambians have been displaced.
</P>
<P>
The donor community should provide assistance to help ease the
pressure on the Zambian government, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to King-Akerele, funding constraints faced by the
World Food Program and the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees have made it impossible to provide refugees with basic
needs and rehabilitate infrastructure leading to camps.
</P>
<P>
In spite of this, she said, the United Nations, the Organization
of Africa Unity and the international community have endorsed
peace efforts in Angola and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
"There is, however, more political and financial support needed
to keep the momentum of U.N. peace missions," she said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day CG meeting, which was attended by representatives
from the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund, the European
Union and a number of donor countries, aims to review and assess
short and long-term economic agenda in the donee countries and
solicit development assistance to Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
