<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea, France Resume Talks on Return of Ancient Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korean and French experts
Tuesday began their third round of talks here on the return of the
Oekyujanggak documents of the medieval Choson Dynasty to South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The South Koran Foreign Affairs and Trade Ministry said the two-
day meeting is expected to resolve the issue before the opening of
the third Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) here in October.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and French Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin agreed to resolve the ancient document issue as soon
as possible during Kim's state visit to France last March.
</P>
<P>
The documents were taken away from the dynastic archives in
Kanghwa Island of South Korea by then French navy during a
military conflict in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
At their second round of meeting last April, the two sides
failed to reach any agreement.
</P>
<P>
At that meeting, South Korea insisted that the documents be
returned while France said the documents are now French property
and that the matter must be solved in a legal manner.
</P>
<P>
The French once proposed the leasing of the documents to South
Korea on a short- or long-term basis, but South Korea rejected the
proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea, Russia to Jointly Protect Seasonal Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Russia have agreed
to form a joint working body to protect seasonal birds, the South
Korean Foreign Affairs and Trade Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the second session of the Korea-
Russia Environment Cooperation Committee held in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will push forward 10 environmental
cooperation projects like a maritime environment protection
project, and strengthen bilateral cooperation among environment
consultative groups in Northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed to strengthen cooperation in the
Northwest Pacific Action Plan, an environment cooperation body
comprising South Korea, Russia, China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, which came to an environment cooperation
treaty and a migrant bird protection accord in 1994, held the
first session of the committee in Moscow in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Their third session will open in Moscow in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
