<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Huge Plunge in Business Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The survey revealed the biggest quarterly plunge in business
confidence in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
The survey of nearly 800 businesses for the three months to
June showed that a net 42 percent of firms expect the general
business situation to worsen during the second half of the year
compared with a net 6 percent in the previous quarter that
expected it to get better.
</P>
<P>
The spectacular fall is blamed on a weak domestic economy, on
higher costs such as petrol, interest rates and the lower currency
increasing the cost of imported goods, tightening profitability
and some government policies.
</P>
<P>
Institute Director Alex Sundakov said that the survey does not
mean the New Zealand economy is slipping into recession but growth
is weak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
