<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Rises Marginally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year rate of
inflation for the month of June increased marginally by 0.6
percent to 59.3 percent despite the inflationary pressures
prevailing in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistical Office Monday said the increases in
food prices accounted for 25.9 percentage points while non-food
items accounted for 33.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in year-on-year inflation was largely accounted
for by increases in the price of fruit and vegetables, bread and
cereals, drink and meat," the office said.
</P>
<P>
It said that "the increase in year-on-year inflation to 59.3
percent from 58.7 percent in May is explained by relatively sharp
increases in June's month-on-month inflation this year by 2.3
percent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
