<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Financial Market Vulnerable to Crisis: Think Tank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Increased foreign capital influx
into the South Korean stock market has made it vulnerable to a
possible crisis, said the Korea Center for International Finance (
KCIF) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report, the KCIF, a government-run organization monitoring
finance and foreign exchange, said the government should make a
contingency plan to deal with a sudden exodus of foreign funds
from the domestic stock market.
</P>
<P>
Refusal to extend 50 billion U.S. dollars of short-term foreign
debt and a withdrawal of 20 percent of foreign investments could
push South Korea back into the economic chaos which it experienced
in late 1997 due to corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners invested 9.63 billion U.S. dollars in the first half
of this year, nearly doubling their total investments last year.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that a government body has issued such
kind of warning although private economic institutes have warned
of a possible economic crisis before.
</P>
<P>
If stock values fall and the South Korean won depreciates,
foreign investors will withdraw their capital out of local stock
markets en masse, and the financial and foreign exchange markets
will be severely destabilized, said the think tank.
</P>
<P>
The likelihood of a second financial crisis cannot be
eliminated completely as local capital can also leave the nation
to minimize foreign exchange losses, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Korea Stock Exchange, as of late June foreign
investors owned 87.7 trillion won (79 billion dollars) worth of
stocks.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts said foreigners would not pull out at
once since they want to avoid the double loss that would occur by
selling stocks and exchanging money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salas has been Suspended for Two Matches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN DIEGO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chile striker Marcelo Salas has
been suspended by FIFA for two international matches for his
serious foul in a 2002 World Cup qualifier against Paraguay,
Chilean Football Association manager Hoffmann announced on Monday
in La Paz, Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
On June 29, Chile played against Paraguay at home in the fourth
round of South American 2002 World Cup qualifier. The famous
striker was shown a red card in the second half for his serious
foul. But the home side eventually beat Paraguay 3-1.
</P>
<P>
Due to the suspension, Salas will have to miss Chile's next two
away matches against Bolivia on July 19th and against Venezuela on
July 25th. But Salas will be fit for the important home match
against Brazil on August 15. 
</P>
