<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahraini Princess Faces Charges of Illegal Entry into U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. immigration judge said
Monday that a Bahraini princess who fled her country to marry a U.
S. Marine must face charges of illegally entering into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Judge Ignacio Fernandez refused to dismiss the charges against
the Bahraini princess, 19-year-old Al Khalifa, with a ruling that
prevents her from applying for permanent residency in the U.S.
without seeking political asylum.
</P>
<P>
She has up to a year under U.S. law to apply for political
asylum.
</P>
<P>
Al Khalifa, who faces extreme persecution for marrying a non-
Muslim if she returns to her country, is planning to apply for
political asylum in the U.S., said her attorney.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Bahraini Embassy in Washington said her
family is eager for her to return and that she would not face
persecution.
</P>
<P>
Al Khalifa, whose father is a cousin of Bahrain's head of state,
Emir Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa, met U.S. Marine Jason Johnson last
year at a mall in the Bahraini capital of Manama, where the 25-
year-old Marine was assigned to a security unit.
</P>
<P>
As Johnson's deployment ended late last year, Al Khalifa used
forged U.S. military documents to fly to the U.S. on a commercial
airplane. She was discovered in Chicago by immigration officials .
</P>
<P>
The couple, who later got married in Las Vegas, now live at
Camp Pendleton, a Marine base 40 miles (64 kilometers) north of
San Diego in California.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini royalty belongs to Islam's mainstream Sunni sect and
rarely marry outside the family circle. Muslim women are not
allowed to marry non-Muslim men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0288 </DOCNO>
