<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Trade Surplus Hits 2.15 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea registered a trade
surplus of 2.15 billion U.S. dollars last month, the Korean
Customs Service announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In June, the nation's exports hit 15.3 billion dollars, up 19.4
percent from the same month last year while imports were 13.15
billion, up 29 percent, with a trade surplus of 2.15 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest monthly trade surplus in the first six
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, South Korean exports stood at 82.
84 billion dollars while imports amounted to 78.59 billion, up 25.
5 percent and 44.7 percent respectively from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
However, the trade surplus decreased 7.42 billion dollars from
the same period a year earlier, down to 4.25 billion.
</P>
<P>
The customs service said high oil prices were the biggest
variable diminishing the trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
The service attributed the dropping trade surplus to increasing
imports, especially oil imports, which hit 11.71 billion in the
first six months of the year, a rise of 105 percent from the same
time of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
