<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring Plan Unveiled to Revitalize Thai Bourse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand (
SET) on Tuesday unveiled a restructuring plan that will split the
bourse into two entities.
</P>
<P>
The first entity will be an operating company to run the daily
affairs of the stock market, while the second will be a foundation
focusing on the development of the local capital market, according
to a SET statement.
</P>
<P>
The exchange's operating unit, which will be a public company
whose shareholders and a board of governors will be current
members of the exchange, will take over the exchange's 10 billion
baht (250 million U.S. dollars) in assets. The board, however,
would have to decide whether to list the company, it said.
</P>
<P>
The unit charged with developing the exchange's business will
operate like a foundation, and use some of the operating company's
assets to build the bourse's infrastructure, it stated.
</P>
<P>
Under the changes, which need a parliamentary amendment of the
Stock Market Act, the exchange's regulatory function would be
separated from its management role, said it.
</P>
<P>
"The SET was set up both as a regulator and operator of the
market. Splitting into an operating company would put the service
focus a lot more clearly on the operations," SET president
Vicharat Vadakan was quoted as saying by the statement.
</P>
<P>
"It would also put SET management on a clearer frame of
accountability to the board and shareholders, and regulatory
functions would largely be placed in the hands of the Securities
and Exchange Commission," Vicharat remarked.
</P>
<P>
"We will retain only that amount of regulation of our members
in order to ensure the integrity of the market," he added.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's benchmark SET index has dropped 35.6 percent this
year, making it the world's fourth worst-performing stock market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
