<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Strives for Emergence of Drug-Free Yangon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is striving for the
emergence of a drug-free region for Yangon division, estimating
that it will be realized after the end of the country's 15-year
plan (1999-2014) of narcotic drug eradication.
</P>
<P>
Measures are being coordinated for implementing the first five-
year project (1999-2004) of the 15-year drug eradication plan in
the Yangon division, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Yangon division commander Major-General Khin Maung Than,
the report said measures to be taken for the short-term five-year
project cover education, treatment, rehabilitation and control of
drug.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should be made in cooperation with departments
concerned in the move area-wise in towns and districts, Khin Maung
Than stressed at a coordination meeting here Monday regarding the
plan.
</P>
<P>
He also called for endeavors to combat narcotic drugs from all
sectors in implementing the project as a national task and to
develop the socio-economic life of the national people of the
border areas and to end poppy cultivation in the areas.
</P>
<P>
After declaring Mongla region in eastern Shan state as a "drug-
free zone in April 1997, Myanmar started implementing the 15-year
plan in 1999, aimed at total eradication of narcotic drug in the
whole country. The plan, which costs 255 million U.S. dollars,
covers 51 drug cultivating and producing townships.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that up to now there remains 89,500 hectares of
poppy cultivation and a total of 86,537 drug addicts in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
As part of its drug control efforts, Myanmar has established
six treatment centers including Yangon, catering to 2,000 addicts
annually, and eight rehabilitation centers for ex-addicts.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics regarding its law enforcement
efforts, in 1999, the Myanmar authorities seized 1,447.55 kilos of
opium, 272.94 kilos of heroin, 274.48 kilos of marijuana, 278.97
liters of phensedyl, 262,542.5 liters of precursor chemicals as
well as 28.75 million tablets of stimulant drugs, destroying 12
heroin refineries.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that the authorities confiscated in
the first five months of this year a total of 1,044 kilos of
narcotic drugs including 678.4 kilos of opium, 20.2 kilos of
heroin and 330.75 kilos of marijuana as well as 3,999 liters of
precursor chemicals and 7.358 million tablets of stimulant drugs
with a total of 1,586 drug-related cases exposed and 2,170 drug
offenders punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Govt Hopeful of All-Party Support for New Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has said her government is hopeful that it will
receive the support of all major political parties to have its
proposed new constitution adopted in Parliament to resolve the
long-running ethnic conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic that all parties, specially the main
opposition United National Party (UNP), will extend their
committed support to make this a reality when it (the new
constitution) is presented in Parliament soon," said Kumaratunga
on Monday, when addressing the inauguration of a project to
provide housing, vocational training and scholarships to members
and families of the service personnel serving in Sri Lanka's north
and east to fight Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said that the government's peaceful negotiations
with 13 political parties on the constitutional reforms is a
landmark approach towards achieving lasting peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
She said that the majority of the Sinhalese and Tamils and
Muslims had recognized their efforts as being sincere and endorsed
them at the last nine provincial and national elections that have
been held.
</P>
<P>
The president has said she would present the proposed new
constitution before Parliament in early August and push it through
before the dissolving of Parliament on August 24. The new
constitution aims to devolve more powers to regions including one
administered by minority Tamils to partly meet the rebel demand of
independence.
</P>
<P>
Tamil Tiger rebels are fighting for a separate homeland called
Eelam for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The government of the ruling People's Alliance and the UNP
reached consensus on the new constitution early this month after
four months of peace talks. Kumaratunga is currently talking with
minority Tamil parties in a bid to hammer out consensus on the new
constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Officials Agree to Allow Flexibility on Tariff Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Senior economic officials of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have agreed to
allow member countries more flexibility on when they participate
in a tariff reduction scheme, a Thai official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The officials, who are attending an ASEAN economic conference
from July 17 to 19 here, will establish a protocol to amend the
Common Effective Preference Tariffs (CEPT) scheme, a tariff-
reduction program that lies at the heart of the ASEAN Free Trade
Area (AFTA), Director-general Karun Kittistaporn of the Business
Economics Department said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The protocol will be forwarded for formal approval to the
upcoming ASEAN economic ministers' meeting in Chiang Mai, Thailand,
in October, said Karun, who heads the Thai delegation at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The proposal of readjusting the CEPT scheme follows Malaysia's
decision to continue to protect its car industry.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has said it intends to delay the transfer of its
vehicle parts from the temporary exclusion list for tariff cuts to
the inclusion list, which was required by the CEPT.
</P>
<P>
The failure to adhere to the original CEPT scheme calls for a
formal regulatory adjustment to the scheme, Karun said.
</P>
<P>
"Since ASEAN works on a compromise basis, the senior officials
have agreed to offer flexible conditions to allow members to delay
transferring their products from the temporary exclusion lists to
the inclusion lists for tariff reduction," he remarked.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, any ASEAN members requesting a delay in
participating in CEPT would be obliged to provide financial
compensation in return as a sign of good will.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN member countries include Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, Laos and
Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
