<HEADLINE> China's Consumer Price Up 0.1 Percent in Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Consumer Price Index (CPI)
edged up 0.1 percent in the first half of this year, a sign of
improvement following continuous falls in the past two years, the
National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) said today.
</P>
<P>
The disposable income of urban residents averaged 3,208 yuan (
386.5 U.S. dollars), a real rise of 7.7 percent from the same
period of last year, Ye Zhen, NBS spokesman, said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Rural residents' cash income averaged 1,013 yuan (122 U.S.
dollars) during the same period, up 1.8 percent. 
