<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rules Out Foreign Troops For Maluku </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian top government
officials Monday reaffirmed that the government will reject
foreign intervention in settling the communal clashes in the
ravaged islands of Maluku.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid disclosed that United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan had telephoned him days earlier and
told him "there had been suggestions about the need for foreign
troops in Maluku."
</P>
<P>
Wahid pointed out that as a sovereign state, Indonesia is fully
responsible for its domestic affairs and it had taken several
measures to end the conflict in Maluku, including imposing a state
of civil emergency in the provinces of Maluku and North Maluku.
</P>
<P>
The president also said, "Kofi will try to ensure that these
proposals (for foreign troops in Maluku) will not be put on the
agenda of the U.N. Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Admitting that events in Maluku had international repercussions,
and thus the whole country needed to work hard to resolve the
crisis, Wahid insisted that Indonesia would reject any foreign
involvement in quelling the fighting in the spice islands.
</P>
<P>
"Only when we are overwhelmed, maybe we will scream for
logistics and equipment only, no more than that. It is the maximum
that we can accept," the president was quoted by the Jakarta Post
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab also ruled out
international intervention in Maluku and North Maluku, but said
Jakarta would welcome humanitarian aid from abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said that some religious leaders in the bloodied islands
have asked the government to invite international forces to help
restore security and order there.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue not to accept that because foreign
intervention is negative in nature and could undermine our
sovereignty," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Shihab said the government will not invite foreign troops,
including a U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
"This is our internal problem. Foreign intervention would give
the impression that the government has failed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister underlined his comments by warning of harsh action
against international forces or groups in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will not hesitate to arrest such groups," he was quoted by
the Indonesian Observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite the state of civil emergency in Maluku and North Maluku,
which took effect last month, violence has continued unabated,
particularly in Ambon, capital of Maluku, and the surrounding
areas.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 people have been killed over the past week and more
than 3,000 people have died since the communal violence erupted in
January 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Announces Another Oil Production Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The OPEC secretariat announced here
Monday that the bloc will boost its oil production by 500,000
barrels a day from the end of July if oil prices remain above the
desired range of 22-28 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the secretariat said if petroleum prices
continue to remain at the current levels till July 28, members of
the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will
increase their output.
</P>
<P>
Crude price hit 28.84 dollars a barrel last Friday, its 10th
straight day above 28 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Under OPEC's so-called "price-band" mechanism designed to
regulate global oil prices, the producers are to raise output
targets by 500,000 barrels a day if the price of the reference
basket of OPEC crude oils exceeds 28 dollars per barrel for 20
consecutive trading days.
</P>
<P>
OPEC President Ali Rodriguez has told oil ministers of the
group to be "prepared to take the necessary steps to raise output.
"
</P>
<P>
If the plan is implemented, production targets for OPEC members,
except Iraq, will rise from 25.4 million to 25.9 million barrels a
day. The additional 500,000 barrels will be attributed among
member countries at the range of increase between 1.96 to 1.97
percent.
</P>
<P>
To contain the rocketing world oil prices caused by
insufficient output increases by OPEC, the group raised output two
times this year in vain.
</P>
<P>
On July 3, Saudi Arabia signaled a daily production increase of
500,000 barrels. Reports said that oil companies in the kingdom
have already started to raise production since last week.
</P>
<P>
The move has temporarily brought down oil prices on the world
market, but the prices bounced back after Venezuela, Iran and some
other OPEC members voiced opposition to the production increase.
</P>
<P>
These countries believe that the hike of oil prices was sparked
by the high prices of petroleum products, gasoline in particular,
on the U.S. and European markets rather than lack of oil supply.
</P>
<P>
After OPEC's announcement, crude futures traded in London
dipped to 28.71 dollars a barrel on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0318 </DOCNO>
