<HEADLINE> Romanian President Not to Run for Re-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu announced on Monday that he will not run for
another term of presidency.
</P>
<P>
In a live broadcast on television, he said that his decision
will enable him to wage a just and firm struggle against
corruption of all kinds in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president also decided not to run for a parliament seat or
head of any political party.
</P>
<P>
But he pledged that he will dedicate his life to protecting the
interests of the country and the people when and if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu's decision surprised the political circles in
Romania. Mincea Ionescu-Quintus, chairman of the National Liberal
Party, described it as a brave decision which will win respects of
the people.
</P>
<P>
However, Teodor Melescanu, chairman of the Alliance for Romania,
holds an opposite viewpoint, saying that the decision means that
the president failed in office for the last four years.
</P>
<P>
The presidential and parliament elections are scheduled for the
end of 2000. Constantinescu has been regarded as a strong
candidate for the next presidency. 
</P>
