<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA -- East Timor will join the Community of the Portuguese-
speaking Countries (CPLP) as its eighth member once it gains full
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Xanana Gusmao, representative of the East Timorese delegation
and observer to the third summit of the CPLP, made the statement
at its opening session in Maputo on Monday, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
"East Timor will surely be the eighth member of the Community
of the Portuguese-speaking Countries", Gusmao said before
presenting the summit leaders with colorful Timorese "tais",
traditional hand-woven scarves. (Angola-East Timor-CPLP)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union on Monday promised not to go to
its planned summit with the western Balkan nations empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Romano Prodi, president of the European Commission, the
executive body of the 15-nation bloc, told visiting Croatian
President Stipe Mesic that the EU member states would open their
markets one-sided toward Croatia prior to the summit that is
slated for November.
</P>
<P>
Trade and stabilization will be promoted as the concrete
preparation for the summit that pools the 15 EU nations with
Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, the Yugoslav
republic of Montenegro and the Yugoslav province of Kosovo. (EU-
Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton wants to wrap up the
Middle East peace talks in Camp David, Maryland, before he leaves
for a Group of Eight (G-8) summit in Japan, the White House said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The plan is to complete this process before the president goes,
" White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters. "The
president has a schedule to keep."
</P>
<P>
According to Lockhart, Clinton is scheduled to leave for Japan
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
"The pace of the discussions has intensified," the spokesman
said at a temporary press center near Camp David. "There have been
two straight very long nights between the sides working through
the difficult issues here." (US-Mideast-G8)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Delegations from Panama and other Central American
countries that began here Monday a two-day meeting to quicken the
signing of a Free Trade Accord (FTA) expressed optimism in
reaching the accord before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
With this accord they hope to open "right away" a free trade
area made up by Central America's six countries with 36 million
residents and which in 1999 carried out exports to the world above
18 billion U.S. dollars. (C.America-Free Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Foreign Office is scheduled to hold a joint
conference on Tuesday with other government and local associations,
trying to find the way to improve the relevance of the European
Union (EU) to British citizen.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office Minister for Europe, Keith Vaz, will co-host the
joint conference between the Foreign Office, Local Government
Association and Local Government International Bureau to discuss
how to bring the EU closer to the Britons.
</P>
<P>
The conference will ensure that the Foreign Office takes full
account of local government needs when negotiating in Brussels and
with partners, a foreign office statement said. (Britain-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Monday that it hoped
Russian President Vladimir Putin would discuss with the leader of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) its missile
program, over which Washington shows grave concern despite its own
plan of deploying the theater missile defense system in the region.
</P>
<P>
President Putin will make a state visit to the DPRK Wednesday
and hold talks with DPRK leader Kim Jong-Il before his departure
for Okinawa to attend a G8 summit.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton's deputy national security adviser, Jim
Steinberg, said Putin's visit to Pyongyang would make a positive
contribution to regional security.(US-Russia-DPRK)
</P>
