<HEADLINE> Brown Unveils Huge Boost For Public Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- British Chancellor Gordon Brown has
unveiled a massive multi-billion pound cash injection for public
services, laying the ground for the next general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Brown told House of Commons Tuesday that police, hospitals,
schools and public transport will all see substantial rises in
their budgets for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Outlining his long-awaited Comprehensive Spending Review, the
chancellor said the state of Britain's public finances is strong
and that unemployment stands at its lowest level for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
He said overall department expenditure limits will rise from
195 billion pounds this year to 246 billion by 2003/04. Total
spending, which includes welfare and interest payments on debt,
will rise from 372 billion pounds this year to 440 billion pounds
by 2003/04.
</P>
<P>
Brown also confirmed net capital investment will more than
double to 18 billion pounds by 2004 and that current spending will
rise by 2.5 percent above inflation.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that further details will be rolled out with
the publication of the 10-year plans for transport later this week
and for the National Health Service next week.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that the announcement will
provide a badly needed fillip for the Labor government after
recent setbacks, culminating in the lead of Tony Blair's memo
revealing fears that he appears to be "out of touch." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
