<HEADLINE> Britain Recalls Fijian High Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain Tuesday recalled its high
commissioner in Fiji for consultations amid government unease at
the deal to end the hostage crisis in Suva, the Fijian capital.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Officer Minister John Battle announced that the British
High Commissioner in Suva Michael Dibben is being recalled to
London for consultations.
</P>
<P>
"We are disturbed that the deal struck to secure the release of
the hostages abrogates the 1997 Constitution and leaves almost
half the population of Fiji without democratic representation,"
Battle said.
</P>
<P>
He said relief at the safe release of all the hostages should
not obscure the fact that the crisis for Fiji is not over.
</P>
<P>
"I am discussing next steps with my Commonwealth and other
international partners, and will also consult our high
commissioner on his return," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
That step meant Britain joined Australia and New Zealand in
recalling its high commissioner from Fiji in protest at the latest
developments in the country's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Fijian high commissioner in London has also been summoned
to the Foreign Office to be told of Britain's concerns about the
formation of a new government in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
Fiji's new cabinet, announced earlier Tuesday, excluded all
ethnic Indians.
</P>
<P>
Australia and New Zealand have already imposed a range of
sanctions on Fiji until full democracy is restored.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the European Union have also threatened
sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
