<HEADLINE> Gore Shows Progress in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
showed progress in national polls before the national conventions
of the Republican Party and the Democratic Party are held.
</P>
<P>
Two polls released Monday demonstrated that Democratic
presidential candidate Gore has closed the gap with Republican
rival George W. Bush after trailing in the majority of polls taken
over the past couple of months.
</P>
<P>
According to a CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, Texas Governor Bush
has the support of 48 percent while Gore enjoys 46 percent among
likely voters. Earlier this month, Bush led Gore 50 percent to 41
percent in that poll, but Gore has moved ahead among women voters
and pulled even among independents.
</P>
<P>
A CBS News poll also showed the race equally close among
registered voters, 43 percent for Bush and 41 percent for Gore. In
May, Bush was at 47 percent and Gore at 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
The national convention of the Republican Party is scheduled
from July 31 to August 3 in Philadelphia, and the Democratic Party
will hold its national convention from August 14 to 17 in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
A political analyst said Gore's emphasis on prosperity during
the Clinton-Gore administration and his plans for continuing it
have helped in his progress in polls.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic National Committee launched a 17-state
advertising effort in early June designed to revive Gore's lagging
campaign. Vice President Gore also visited several states in a "
prosperity tour" to attract the voters' attention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
