<HEADLINE> Scientists: CJD Deaths Will Rise By 30 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Deaths from the human form of mad
cow disease are expected to increase by up to 30 percent over
coming years, British scientists said.
</P>
<P>
Between two and four more people will probably die from new
variant CJD in addition to the 10 to 15 deaths currently
experienced each year, said Professor Peter Smith.
</P>
<P>
Smith, acting head of the Spongiform Encephalopathy Advisory
Committee, told BBC Radio 4' Today program that this is borne out
by a "statistically significant" increase in cases.
</P>
<P>
"There are now 76 definite and probable cases, including seven
probables still alive," the committee said in a statement released
recently.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a trend upwards and we have just seen analyses
showing that that trend upwards now is formally statistically
significant and is unlikely to be due to chance," it added.
</P>
<P>
Last month the government launched an urgent inquiry into a
cluster of CJD deaths around the small village of Queniborough in
the central English county of leicestershire.
</P>
<P>
Robert Will, head of the government's CJD surveillance unit,
said at the weekend that baby food and school meals may have been
a major source for the Queniborough outbreak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000718.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
