<HEADLINE> Inflation in Mexico to Go Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will close year 2000
with 9.2 percent of inflation rate, below the 10 percent target
established at the year's beginning, said Tuesday President of
Bank of Mexico Gullermo Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
July's inflation will be of 0.4 percent, below June's 0.59
percent, predicted Ortiz to the press.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the change of government when new President Vicente
Fox takes possession, coming December 1, Ortiz discarded an
alteration in the central bank's targets, like achieving 3 percent
inflation for year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Ortiz confirmed he's met president elect's economic team for a
tight cooperation in finance and monetary matters.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the exchange market, Ortiz considered uncertainty
overcome with the recovery of stability of Mexico's currency,
the peso, at 9.31 units per dollar, which broke the 10 peso
barrier before the July 2 elections.
</P>
<P>
Ortiz rejected that Mexico's economy is overheated owing to
second three-monthly period results, although there persist risks
due to excessive increase in consumption.
</P>
<P>
He discarded that an eventual rise in interest rates in United
States, of 0.25 percent at end of August or 0.50 at end year 2000
would bear negative repercussions for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
United States is Mexico's main trading partner. 
</P>
