<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Issues Remain Unsolved in Burundi Peace Process: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela said Wednesday there are still two issues
left unresolved in the Burundi peace negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The two issues, namely who is to lead the transitional
government, and the signing of a power-sharing ceasefire agreement,
have to be agreed upon by the warring parties, said Mandela, who
attended a one-day consultative summit in Tanzania's northern town
of Arusha on the Burundi peace negotiation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We've asked the Burundians themselves to agree as to who is to
lead the transitional government," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He added once the two issues are resolved, the way will be
crystal clear for a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
As to the effect of the absence of the rebel National
Liberation Force, a splinter Hutu group of the Hutu People's
Liberation Party (PALIPEHUTU) at Wednesday's meeting, Mandela said:
"Jean Bosco Ndayikengurukiye ( leader of another major rebel group
CNDD-FDD ) was here for the meeting, and he is leading the largest
rebel group inside Burundi and was very supportive."
</P>
<P>
He also said a draft peace agreement was distributed to all
parties in preparation for the final signing, which is scheduled
to fall on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Fighting in Burundi has claimed at least 200,000 lives, mostly
civilians, since it began in October 1993 when Tutsi paratroopers
assassinated the country's first democratically elected president
Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu.
</P>
<P>
Mandela took over as mediator last December from late Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere and has been trying to speed up the talks,
which have dragged on since July 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mandela invited all the Hutu rebel groups that had been
previously excluded to take part in the peace process.
Negotiations over the past 24 months in Arusha have worked out the
outlines of a peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
