<HEADLINE> Zanzibar President Vows to Ensure Peaceful Elections  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour on Wednesday expressed his government's determination to
ensure the forthcoming general elections to be conducted
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Addressing members of the House of Representatives in the semi-
autonomous region of Tanzania, the president urged the people not
to be swayed by radical speeches given by some politicians, saying
that his government will no longer tolerate acts to plunge the
nation into violence.
</P>
<P>
"We will act tough against those who will disrupt peace and
unity," Salmin stressed, adding that the Zanzibaris will commit a
big "sin" to entertain violence and later seek "sanctuary" in
other nations.
</P>
<P>
The isles leader said the elections, to be held on October 29
simultaneously in Zanzibar and mainland Tanzania, are aimed at
enabling the people to pick their suitable leaders and should not,
under any circumstances, be taken as a ticket to seek political
revenge.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Salmin also reminded the MPs that the future of
Zanzibar lies on the Zanzibaris themselves, warning that the
people should be careful to avoid playing with a political fire,
saying "it is dangerous and can burn".
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania after a revolt in 1964 that ousted the sultan
and Omani Arabs who ruled the islands.
</P>
<P>
It is a semi-autonomous state with its own government and
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Salmin became the Zanzibar President in 1990, and was reelected
in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
