<HEADLINE> S. Africa Wants Social Intervention in Combating AIDS: Minister  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa sees social
intervention as an important weapon in the fight against AIDS,
Health Minister Manto Tshabalala-Msimang said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Social interventions -- the mainstay of primary prevention
efforts -- remain the most potent weapon in our fight against this
scourge," said the minister, adding that the temptation to see HIV/
AIDS in only a medical context should be resisted.
</P>
<P>
"This is not... meant to disregard the importance of medical
intervention in improving the quality of life of those with this
disease, but rather an appeal for us not to lose sight of the fact
that this is essentially a social disease," she said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tshabalala-Msimang reaffirmed President Thabo Mbeki'
s assertion that any response to the HIV/AIDS epidemic, to be
comprehensive and sustainable, had to be located within the
reality of the prevailing twin scourges of poverty and disease.
</P>
<P>
"The battle against HIV and AIDS has to be won, and therefore
will be fought tenaciously on all fronts that employ affordable,
effective and sustainable strategies.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard prevention remains our vanguard, while we
continue to work tirelessly to investigate other options and
interventions," she said.
</P>
<P>
As far as South Africa's health status, socio-economic
situation and level of infrastructure development are concerned,
no other weapon would in the long term achieve the benefits that
prevention would, she said.
</P>
<P>
As to the 13th international AIDS conference held in Durban,
Tshabalala-Msimang said the conference was a success and had met
the goals of the government.
</P>
<P>
Unlike previous conferences, which were held in the developed
countries and focused on the challenges of the developed world,
this one had a strong African character.
</P>
<P>
Among the features of the conference was "the focus on the
unacceptability of the continued marginalization of those from
developing countries with respect to access to drugs", the
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
