<HEADLINE> S. African President Leaves for Japan to Address G8 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki left the country on Wednesday for Japan to pinpoint African
problems at the G8 summit in Tokyo on July 21, the Presidential
Office said.
</P>
<P>
The president is among a delegation of leaders from various
organizations of the developing countries. Other members of the
delegation include Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika,
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, Thailand's Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
The mandate to represent the interests of Africa was given to
President Mbeki and to President Bouteflika of Algeria by the
Extraordinary Summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
held in Sirte in Libya in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will press forward the need for developed
countries to seriously address issues of concern to the developing
countries, primarily efforts to ensure people-centered development
and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Within the context of globalization, the G8 Summit is seen as an
important organization for convincing wealthy countries of the
need to enter into partnerships for the development of the
developing countries, especially Africa.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which involves this delegation of the developing
countries and the G8 leaders will be the first of its kind.
</P>
