<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Urges EU to Lift Ban on Fish Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Public Health Minister Sam
Ongeri has urged the European Union (EU) to lift the ban on Kenya'
s fish exportation as the country's fish industry has met the
hygienic standards required.
</P>
<P>
When meeting a European Parliament delegation here on Tuesday,
Ongeri said his ministry has put in place measures to ensure that
fish processing is done in accordance with international standards,
media here reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Public health officials have been ordered to conduct routine
checks to ensure that fish processing is done in high hygienic
standards, he said.
</P>
<P>
The export of fresh fish from Kenya to the EU was banned in
January 1998 on the grounds of poor hygienic conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to Ongeri, the ban has led to heavy losses and
increased poverty levels. The ban is causing Kenya a loss of 5
billion shillings (about 65 million U.S. dollars) annually, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ulla Sandeback, one of the delegation members, told Ongeri that
they would raise the matter with the European Commission and the
European Council of Ministers. 
</P>
