<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Pledges Free and Peace Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye has reiterated his government's stance to ensure
the upcoming general elections be held freely and peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Winding up the five-year term parliament in the central town of
Dodoma on Tuesday, the premier assured the nation that the
elections on October 29 will be held peacefully and the National
Electoral Commission will be allocated adequate funds to conduct
the exercise.
</P>
<P>
"We should all feel proud to see the elections go through
peacefully to consolidate national unity and solidarity," Sumaye
told the Members of Parliament elected in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The premier, who is also leader of government business in
legislature, challenged political parties and other civic
societies to educate people on the importance of registering and
casting their votes.
</P>
<P>
Registration of voters will officially begin on August 8 and
end on August 28 this year, Sumaye said, calling on eligible
voters to turn up en masse for registration and vote on the
polling day.
</P>
<P>
The current parliament will be officially dissolved by
President Benjamin Mkapa on August 4. The first parliamentary
session after the elections will be held in Dodoma on November 14.
</P>
<P>
The coming elections will be the second multiparty elections in
Tanzania. The last one was held in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In that election, Mkapa of the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi party
defeated three candidates from the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
