<HEADLINE> Violent Crime Increases in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A dramatic rise in violent crime
was revealed in the government's latest figures, while overall
crime has risen by nearly four percent, the BBC reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Home Office figures for England and Wales showed a total of 5.3
million offenses reported to the police in 1999-2000 compared to 5.
1 million in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw stressed that Labour was determined
to be tough on crime.
</P>
<P>
"We came into government with a promise to be tough on crime
and tough on the causes of crime, this is not an empty slogan at
all," he told BBC.
</P>
<P>
But the Conservatives strongly criticized the government over
the new figures, blaming them on falling police numbers.
</P>
<P>
Although acknowledging that there were serious problems with
the number of violent crimes and robberies, Straw said police
targeting of car crime and burglaries had seen both drop.
</P>
<P>
Promising to bear down on crime caused by drunken behavior,
Straw said: "There is a really serious problem about alcohol and
violence.
</P>
<P>
Straw also called on police forces around the country to follow
the example of those forces where crime had actually fallen over
the last year, without the use of additional resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
