<HEADLINE> Guatemalan President Mandate Disapproved :Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Guatemalan President Alfonso
Portillo's mandate is disapproved by 65 percent of the population,
according to a survey of Vox company.
</P>
<P>
Governmental work was approved by 31.2 percent, and 3.7
percent avoided opinion. This was confirmed in the consultation
carried out for 3 Guatemalan dailies, according to reports coming
from Guatemala's capital Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vox Latina said the study has an error margin of 5 percent and
is based on interviews of 210 people.
</P>
<P>
Of those consulted, 26 percent considered Portillo's work
better than that of previous leader, Alovaro Arzu, while 26
percent avoided replying.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Guatemala's situation, 69.1 percent of those
interviewed said that "nothing has changed" since Portillo's
assuming January 14, while 27.8 percent gave a favorable opinion.
</P>
<P>
There's no belief of Portillo's offers or conferences for 73.1
percent, and 23.5 percent thought the opposite and the rest
avoided answering.
</P>
<P>
Of those interviewed, 82.7 considered the governor's campaign
commitments regarding security unfulfilled, said Vox Latina in
its study.  
</P>
