<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Lower On Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stock ended lower
Tuesday as investors took some profits from a rally in the
previous sessions after the release of the June Consumer Price
Index report.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 64.35 at 10,739.92.
The blue chip index fell 8.48 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 97.50 at 4,177.17 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 16.75 at 1,493.74.
</P>
<P>
The market fell as investors cashed in profits from the gains
in the industrial and technology sectors after the Labor
Department released the CPI report in June. The report said the
overall CPI jumped a higher-than-expected 0.6 percent in June but
the code CPI, which excludes the volatile energy and food
categories, rose just 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that inflation remains tame but the new
data failed to clear up uncertainty about the Federal Reserve's
next move on interest rates although Wall Street analysts expected
the central bank to leave the rates unchanged at the August 22
meeting. The Federal Reserve has raised rates six times in the
past 13 months and the rate hikes were slowing the U.S. economy
and inflation remains under control.
</P>
<P>
Because of the profit-taking by investors, chipmaker Intel,
software giant Microsoft and Apple Computer fell ahead of their
earnings report release later today, driving the whole market
lower.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 4.99 at 658.21 and the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 8.90 at 536.28. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 0.09 at 943.75.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New Stock Exchange, with 1,683 down, 1,195 up and 498
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 905.33 million shares from 900.37
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
