<HEADLINE> Microsoft Earnings Beat Analyst Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft reported Tuesday its
fourth-quarter earnings of 5.76 billion U.S. dollars, beating
analyst expectations by 2 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of analysts expected the software giant to earn
42 cents per share on revenue of 5.6 billion dollars for the
quarter. Analysts predicted that the company's unusually high
sales reported one year ago would be hard to top. They have been
also closely watching the sales of Windows 2000 operating system
which was launched in February because it is a key indicator of
the health of not only Microsoft, but the PC industry as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Seattle-based company reported 22.92 billion dollars for
the entire fiscal year that ended June 30, up 16 percent from
revenue of the previous year. Net income for the year totaled 9.42
billion dollars, compared with 7.79 billion dollars for the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Strong corporate sales of its Windows 2000 operating system
drove fourth-quarter earnings, the company said.
</P>
<P>
"We experienced another record year of business results despite
many challenges," Microsoft said in a statement, pointing to
growth in Asia and its consumer business. "Although we remain
guarded in the near term about business PC growth rates, we look
forward to the tremendous opportunity in front of us with the
Windows 2000 generation of server products."
</P>
<P>
The company reiterated its claim to have seized the traffic
lead for Internet properties. The MSN network recorded 19 percent
year-over-year growth in U.S. audience reach. The company's ISP,
MSN Internet Access, now has 3 million members, a 20 percent
improvement from a year ago, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
