<HEADLINE> Brazil Making Efforts to Reduce Impact of Spilt Crude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian government is making
effort to reduce the environmental impact of 4 million liters of
oil spillage, occurred last Sunday in Parana state.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry said Tuesday that the oil company has already
briefed heads of embassies of Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay in
Brasilia the government's determination to this regard.
</P>
<P>
"Brazilian authorities are making every effort to bring down
the accident's impact on national land and avoid that spilt crude
goes beyond national borders", affirmed Brazil's Foreign Ministry'
s item.
</P>
<P>
In the document, Brazil's government commits itself to send to
authorities of the 3 neighboring countries all technical data
relative to the spillage, besides keeping them well informed about
measures taken to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Refinery Getulio Vargas Refinery's oil spillage is considered
the greatest ecological disaster in Parana state. Stains of
spilled crude are moving forward at a speed of 500 to 800 meters
an hour in Iguazu river, which crosses Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of workers dug runoff channels and strung barriers
across the Iguacu River on Tuesday in a race to contain the
country's worst oil spill in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
By mid-afternoon Tuesday, the black stain had moved about 40
kilometers downstream from the Getulio Vargas oil refinery in
Araucaria, where a burst pipe on Sunday spewed more than 1 million
gallons ( 33,000 barrels) of crude oil into a tributary of the
Iguacu in southern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists said their goal was to keep the spill from
reaching Uniao da Vitoria, about 200 kilometers below the slow-
moving slick. The city of 70,000 people depends on the Iguacu for
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
The oil was advancing at about 1 kilometer per hour, and there
was little chance it would reach postcard-famous Iguacu Falls,
650 kilometers away near Brazil's western border with Paraguay and
Argentina, environmentalists said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
