<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- German tourist Renate Wallert
arrived in Frankfurt on Tuesday after being held hostage for three
months by Muslim separatist guerrilla in the southern Phippine
island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
the 56-year-old teacher was released on Monday by the Abu
Sayyaf organization, which still detained her husband, son and
other 16 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf guerrilla kidnapped the Wallert family and
other people from a Malaysian tourist resort.
</P>
<P>
Wallert looked pale and exhaust from the long captivity in
harsh jungles when she emerged out of the special plane which
brought her back from the Phillipines.
</P>
<P>
She would be interviewed by German legal authorities as a
witness and victim of the kidnapping which is the subject of a
criminal investigation underway, according press reports here.
</P>
<P>
Upon her release, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said
that he was happy at the news and but still felt concerns for
other hostages. He hoped that the mediation efforts by the
Phillipine government would result the release of all hostages.
</P>
<P>
The German government denied reports that it has paid ransom
for the release of Wallert. 
</P>
