<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Reach Agreement on Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Japan
have reached an agreement to settle a telecommunications trade row,
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement ... was reached as part of the Enhanced
Initiative on Deregulation," Barshefsky said in a telephone press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"This deal opens Japan's telecommunications market to genuine
competition and should save telecommunications carriers around the
world more than two billion dollars over the next two years," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the agreement, President Bill Clinton said that "this
important agreement will help further reduce regulatory barriers
to trade between the United States and Japan."
</P>
<P>
"It is a win-win for the United States and Japan and represents
an important step as we prepare to discuss the impact of
information technology on the global economy at the (Group of
Eight) summit," Clinton said in a statement read by Barshefsky at
the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan were scrambling to stop a row over
the interconnection fees charged by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp. that had been overshadowing this week's Group of Eight
summit to be held in Okinawa, Japan. 
</P>
