<HEADLINE> No UK Trial for IRA Suspect  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Roisin McAliskey, an Irish
Republican Army suspect, will not face trial in Britain in
connection with a bombing of British army barracks, it was
announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Crown Prosecution Service ruled there was not enough
evidence to justify trying Ms McAliskey, 26, over the attack on
the barracks in Osnabruck, Germany, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
There were also fears that it had been too long since the
alleged offense for a trial to take place, under British law.
</P>
<P>
The decision, endorsed by the Attorney General and Solicitor
General, was revealed to Parliament on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ms McAliskey, daughter of former MP Bernadette McAliskey, is
still wanted for questioning by German police over the attack,
which damaged several buildings.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw caused a political storm two years
ago when he ruled she was too ill to be extradited.
</P>
<P>
Ms McAliskey had been pregnant when she was arrested and was
diagnosed with post-natal depression during the extradition
process.
</P>
<P>
But she could still have been prosecuted in the UK under the
terms of a European counter-terrorism agreement. 
</P>
