<HEADLINE> African Leaders Satisfied With Burundi Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Six regional heads of state
who attended a one-day consultative summit in Tanzania's northern
town of Arusha on Wednesday expressed satisfaction with the result
of their negotiations aimed at ending the seven-year-old bloodshed
in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the negotiations have entered into a very
advanced and encouraging stage.
</P>
<P>
Among those who present the summit were Ugandan President and
Chairman of the Great Lakes Initiative on Burundi Yoweri Museveni,
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi, Burundian
President Pierre Buyoya and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued at the end of the six-hour
close-door meeting, the heads of state met separately with heads
of the 19 Burundian negotiating parties and called upon them to
redouble their efforts and commitment to the negotiations "in the
spirit of give and take so as to resolve all outstanding
differences".
</P>
<P>
The summit commended peace facilitator and former South African
President Nelson Mandela, members of his facilitation team and the
Burundian negotiating parties, whose efforts and commitments have
made the progress possible.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, dissident Hutu rebel leader jean-Bosco
Ndayikengurukiye has come to Arusha, where he has been holding
private talks with the facilitation team. He met Mandela on
Wednesday and held his first direct talks with Burundian President
Buyoya on a ceasefire in the country's seven-year civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
