<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Declares State of Emergency in Northern Part of Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles Taylor
Wednesday declared a "state of emergency" in northern part of the
country where government troops have been battling dissident
forces for more than a week, according to the Pan-African News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a broadcasting speech that the state of
emergency, declared in consultation with the parliament, will
cover areas in northern Lofa County within the conflict zone.
</P>
<P>
Over a week ago, the government announced that dissident forces
had entered the country from Guinea and attacked the key
provincial town of Voinjama, some 220 kilometers from Liberia's
capital Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said in the speech in Moronvia: "Fellow Liberians, I
will not deceive you, enemy forces continue to occupy Voinjama and
a few towns around the city and fighting is still going on."
</P>
<P>
The president disclosed that he has ordered all able-bodied men
and women with combat experience to report to various regional
bases in an on-going mobilization exercise and pledged that "not
one inch of Liberian soil will be occupied by anyone in an
unfriendly posture."
</P>
<P>
Taylor said the invading forces have "constant supplies coming
out of Guinea" so it was important that Guinean President Lansana
Conteh "acts urgently in helping to resolve this matter."
</P>
<P>
He cited that the attack was the third on Liberia from Guinea "
most probably with the acquiescence of that government...three
strikes, I think that is enough."
</P>
<P>
Taylor said Liberia has launched formal complaints to the
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan, explaining the three
attacks from Guinea on Liberian territory. 
</P>
